(316, 1, '2010-12-06 02:22:52', '2010-12-06 02:22:52', '<script src="http://connect.facebook.net/en_US/all.js#xfbml=1"></script><fb:like show_faces="true" width="450"></fb:like>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div id="rating-block">\r\n\r\n[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="2.5" cat1detail="Utilitarian coffee perfect for those all-night-ers." cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="3" cat2detail="Couches, bar and tables abound; lots of windows."]\r\n<table id="info">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="title">Features <a title="key" href="http://coffeebot.co/about-2/symbol-key/">(Key)</a></td>\r\n<td><span class="no-atm">No ATM</span><span class="no-alcohol">No Alcohol</span><span class="live-music">Live Music</span><span class="yes-parking">Free Parking</span><span class="yes-food">Food is Served</span><span class="yes-wifi">Free Wifi</span><span class="manual">Manual Espresso Machine</span>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="address">1795 Folsom St., Boulder, CO 80302</td>\r\n<td class="phone">(303) 440-8808</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="website"><a title="Folsom St Coffee" href="http://www.folsomstreetcoffee.com/">Website</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<span class="first-words">Bot1 had just completed a lecture at CU on the intricacies of wiring a common household goldfish,</span> and like he is after every lecture, found his system needing a certain caffeine boost. We found ourselves at Folsom St. Coffee Co. This is a college joint through and through, and the day we visited it was its usual self: packed, hip...and green. According to their website, Folsom St. Coffee is “Boulder''s only true eco-friendly coffeehouse. Folsom St. Coffee Co. was awarded the Eco-Cycle award for ''Zero Waste or Darn Near'' as well as the "Waste Reduction" award from the Center For Resource Conservation.” I believe it, because when Bot1 tried to throw away his trash, his waste eliminating algorithm caused his CPU to overheat just trying to sort out which tub to throw what in.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee.</span> As has become customary, a double espresso was ordered and Bot1 left to talk up a couple students who were sitting outside. The espresso presented to me had a deceivingly beautiful thick crema that held fast when I spooned some sugar on top. That was a good sign. The flavor, however, was a disappointment. Oddly enough I felt like I was drinking a lime. Of course there were most of the typical espresso qualities, but the acidity was shocking! I''d like to attribute this to the extraction of the shot, but I watched it pour and everything was on the up and up. The flavor evened out when it was in an Americano, but overall I wasn''t too impressed with the flavor.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere.</span>Like many coffee shops, however, the experience doesn''t always center around the coffee, and ultimately Folsom St. Coffee delivered in other areas. The atmosphere was welcoming, cozy and was the sort of place in which I felt I could get motivated to finally write my 20 page single-spaced essay on the relationship between Pyongyang and Beijing. The muddled and haphazard decor actually cemented the cozy feeling, and that constant murmur of a packed coffee house was ideal for working, meeting friends, or simply sipping a cup of coffee. Complete with poetry, open mic nights and live music acts, this place is hopping a good part of every day, and the sort of place young hipsters like to frequent.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The End.</span> Overall this coffee shop is very enjoyable, and despite being turned down three whole times, Bot1 vowed it wouldn''t keep him down and will definitely return. While the coffee didn''t bowl me over, if you keep it to lattes, Americanos, teas and brews you won''t be disappointed. <span class="end-icon">END</span>\r\n\r\n[mappress mapid="6"]', 'Folsom St. Coffee Company', 'Bot1 had just completed a lecture at CU on the intricacies of wiring a common household goldfish, and like he is after every lecture, found his system needing a certain caffeine boost. We found ourselves at Folsom St. Coffee Co. ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'folsom-st-coffee-company', '', '', '2011-01-28 21:14:46', '2011-01-28 21:14:46', '', 0, 'http://coffeebot.co/?p=316', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(159, 1, '2010-09-02 18:48:10', '2010-09-02 18:48:10', '<span style="color:#993300;font-family:''ChunkFiveRegular'';font-size:1.6em; font-weight:normal;">It is no secret to those who know me (Bot2) that I really do love coffee.</span> What I’m not sure of, however, is what I love more: the consumable product, or the atmosphere it’s consumed in.\r\n\r\nThe love of the two is my inspiration behind this blog. No false pretenses, no agendas, no long <span style="color:#993300;font-family:''ChunkFiveRegular'';font-size:1.6em; font-weight:normal;">loquacious</span> sentences, just some chatting about coffee and the coffee culture. Ultimately, this site should serve as a resource for people looking for new and exciting coffee shops. Plain and simple.\r\n\r\nYou may be wondering if I even know anything about coffee. Yes, yes I do. Then again, no, no I don’t. In the “yes” camp, I have over 10 years experience working in the coffee business. I built and ran a coffee shop early this millennium and upon moving to a new suburban area, I spent my time working for various shops while going to school. In the “no” camp, I know that coffee is not a stagnant entity easy to sum up. Coffee is more than just 98% water; it’s a culture, a way of life, a multidimensional beverage that changes by the seasons, countries and political uprisings. It is this complex personality that I love about coffee-always changing and morphing, yet somehow staying comfortably familiar regardless the venue in which it''s consumed.\r\n\r\nThat''s enough about me. The true hero is <a href="http://www.coffeebot.co/?page_id=107">Bot1</a>', 'About', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'about-2', '', '', '2010-11-14 18:31:29', '2010-11-14 18:31:29', '', 0, 'http://localhost/coffeebot/?page_id=2', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(160, 1, '2010-09-05 16:09:52', '2010-09-05 16:09:52', '<a href="http://www.coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/09/forza.jpg"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-280" title="forza" src="http://www.coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/09/forza.jpg" alt="Forza Coffee" width="528" height="200" /></a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<div id="rating-block">\r\n\r\n[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="3.5" cat1detail="The employees seem to care &amp; their product, and the result is a decent product." cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="3.5" cat2detail="Lot''s of seating, fireplace, power outlets, local art, competent interior design."]\r\n<table id="info">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="title">Features <a title="key" href="http://www.coffeebot.co/?page_id=195">(Key)</a></td>\r\n<td><span class="no-atm">No ATM</span><span class="no-alcohol">No Alcohol</span><span class="no-music">No Music</span><span class="yes-parking">Free Parking</span><span class="yes-food">Food is Served</span><span class="yes-wifi">Free Wifi</span><span class="manual">Manual Espresso Machine</span>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="address">3013 W. 104th Ave., Westminster, CO 80031</td>\r\n<td class="phone">(303) 465-0605</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="website"><a title="Forza Coffee" href="http://www.rmforzacoffee.com">Website</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<span class="first-words">I was trying to decide which coffee house to review first for CoffeeBot.</span> Not the most easy decision to make considering here in the Denver metro area we have close to 10 x 8 to the third carry the two coffee shops. OK, not that many, but still. Luckily, Bot1 made the decision for me, and it''s a good one: Forza Coffee in Westminster. I know, I know, a suburban coffee shop, but bear with me...<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The History</span> From what I know about this place, its pedigree is traced back to Tacoma, Washington—not a bad place to come from, I suppose. Their self-description talks of being a vital part of the community and being inspired by Italy''s espresso culture, yada yada yada. Nearly everyone says that. Even Howard Schultz said that at one time and look where that got us. However, their expressed desire to be a neighborhood coffee shop seems to actually be working.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee</span> My standard first-time drink is usually an Americano or latte. In this case, the Americano is a wonderful baseline drink. If made correctly, you get a lovely crema, the hot water and espresso combination even out the flavor of the coffee, and let''s face it: espresso is gone way too fast. I''m not Italian, for Pete''s sake. I love espresso shots but will only drink it straight in places I really trust. To my delight, I heard the familiar banging of portafilters into bins, and I had a feeling I was in for a treat. The drink was produced and brought to my table, whereupon I viewed that  nice layer of crema. The flavor was good. Not amazing, but good. The espresso certainly embodied everything a fine espresso should: full body, slight bitterness, subtle caramel tones; but for me, the dimension didn''t go far enough. That''s hardly a negative, since the intensity of espresso is, after all, subjective.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere</span> For once, this is a suburban coffee shop that is actually comfortable and has a hint of urban dinge that in my opinion, all the best coffee shops have. Sometimes, the dingier the better. The deep yellow-gold, black, copper and dark wood mix well to form a comfortable and inspiring atmosphere. Armed with a great comfy-couch area and plenty of tables (including outside seating) you definitely have your choice of places to sit. Mine, however, was by the fireplace. And that''s enough about the design, I drink coffee, after all.\r\n<span class="first-words">The End</span> Finally, the experience was punctuated by genuinely nice staff. I''ve been a few times, and even Bot1 has sneaked over there a couple times when I haven''t been looking. Witty small talk and a staff that calls  you by name on the second visit is a good step in the direction of having a lasting neighborhood coffee shop.<span class="end-icon">END</span>\r\n[mappress mapid="3"]\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>', 'Forza Coffee', 'I was trying to decide which coffee house to review first for Coffee-Bot. Not the most easy decision to make considering here in the Denver metro area we have close to 10 x 8 to the third carry the two...coffee shops. OK, not that many, but still. Luckily, Bot1 made the decision for me, and it''s a good one: Forza Coffee in Westminster. I know, I know, a suburban coffee shop, but bear with me...', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'forza-coffee', '', '', '2011-01-28 21:28:46', '2011-01-28 21:28:46', '', 0, 'http://localhost/coffeebot/?p=3', 0, 'post', '', 0),
