(244, 1, '2010-09-02 18:48:10', '2010-09-02 18:48:10', '<span style="color:#993300;font-family:''ChunkFiveRegular'';font-size:1.6em; font-weight:normal;">It is no secret to those who know me (Bot2) that I really do love coffee.</span> What I’m not sure of, however, is what I love more: the consumable product, or the atmosphere it’s consumed in.\n\nThe love of the two is my inspiration behind this blog. No false pretenses, no agendas, no big <span style="color:#993300;font-family:''ChunkFiveRegular'';font-size:1.6em; font-weight:normal;">loquacious</span> words, just some chatting about coffee and the coffee culture. Ultimately, this site should serve as a resource for people looking for new and exciting coffee shops. Plain and simple.\n\nYou may be wondering if I even know anything about coffee. Yes, yes I do. Then again, no, no I don’t. In the “yes” camp, I have over 10 years experience working in the coffee business. I built and ran a coffee shop early this millennium and upon moving to a new suburban area, I spent my time working for various shops while going to school. In the “no” camp, I know that coffee is not a stagnant entity easy to sum up. Coffee is more than just 98% water; it’s a culture, a way of life, a multidimensional beverage that changes by the seasons, countries and political uprisings. It is this complex personality that I love about coffee-always changing and morphing, yet somehow staying comfortably familiar regardless the venue in which it''s consumed.\n\nThat''s enough about me. The true hero is <a href="http://localhost/coffeebot/?page_id=107">Bot1</a>', 'About', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '159-revision', '', '', '2010-09-02 18:48:10', '2010-09-02 18:48:10', '', 159, 'http://coffeebot.co/?p=244', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(245, 1, '2010-11-14 17:18:17', '2010-11-14 17:18:17', '<p style="text-align: center;">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"></p>\r\n\r\n<hr /><a href="http://localhost/coffeebot/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/paris-platte.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-138" title="Paris On The Platte" src="http://localhost/coffeebot/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/paris-platte.jpg" alt="Paris On The Platte" width="530" height="200" /></a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<div id="rating-block">\r\n\r\n[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="3" cat1detail="Utilitarian caffeine with modest attention to quality." cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="3.5" cat2detail="Dark where it needs to be, light where it''s important, local art and aged/warehouse character"]\r\n<table id="info">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="title">Features <a title="key" href="http://localhost/coffeebot/?page_id=195">(Key)</a></td>\r\n<td><span class="alcohol">Alcohol</span><span class="food">Food</span><span class="paid-parking">Free parking</span><span class="wifi">WiFi</span><span class="manual">Manual Machine</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="address">1553 Platte St, Denver, CO 80202</td>\r\n<td class="phone">(303) 455-2451</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="website"><a title="Paris On The Platte" href="http://www.parisontheplattecafeandbar.com">Website</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<span class="first-words">Paris on the Platte is one of my favorite urban coffee bars in the Denver metro.</span> It has all the great ''cool factors'': local art that is usually good, a store-front facing a lively street, weathered decor,  indie rock (I walked in to Viva Voce playing over the speakers—one of my favorite bands), citizens in skinny jeans, and decent espresso. It''s a great place being not only a coffee shop, but also a cafe and bar.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee</span> Bot1 showed up in a pair of skinny jeans he had purchased from the Salvation Army, and after I wrestled them off of him, he sulked up to the counter and ordered a small latte. Even though we ordered a small, it came in a nice big mug, and after some detailed chemical analysis, Bot1 concluded the cinnamon on top of the foam was in fact, cinnamon. A nice touch, but if you don''t like people putting spices on your coffee, you might mention that upon ordering. After this, he lost interest, went over to the bar, and I was left to do the tasting by myself.\r\n\r\nThe latte was...good; nothing amazing. The foam was a tad bubbly and I would have liked more espresso presence, but the flavor that was there was smooth and balanced, so I can''t really complain. This isn''t an artisan place, so I didn''t detect much passion for coffee itself; I understand that coffee passion isn''t necessarily the point to the place.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere</span> The main thing about this joint is that you can come in, set up your lappy, and do what you do best: hit up Facebook. Keep in mind that most people who sit there for a while are also on their laptops, so the connection speed is pretty slow. So, if you''re heading there to play Warcraft, it might not be the best place. Then again, you probably wouldn''t actually head outside to go to a coffee shop, either.\r\n\r\nAnother great aspect is the presence of living, breathing people (not just spoiled robots), and at this place, the flow of humans is pretty constant. Of all the times I have visited, I''ve never seen it empty, and I like that. The steady murmur of conversation is the perfect soundtrack to get my work done. It definitely is a neighborhood staple, and you aren''t without choices on where to sit or plug in. There''s plenty of room in the coffee side, bar side, and there''s even a little patio outback where cigarettes tend to be smoked.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The End</span> Overall, it''s a good place, and I find myself recommending it often. Bot1 even likes it, but I can''t be sure the presence of wine next door is not swaying his judgment.<span class="end-icon">END</span>\r\n\r\n[mappress mapid="4"]', 'Paris on the Platte Cafe &amp; Bar', 'Paris on the Platte is one of my favorite urban coffee bars in the Denver metro. It has all the great ''cool factors'': local art that is usually good, a store-front facing a busy, lively street, beaten-up decor,  indie rock (I walked in to Viva Voce playing-one of my fav''s), citizens in skinny jeans, and decent espresso. It''s a unique place being not only a coffee shop, but also a wine bar.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '121-revision-2', '', '', '2010-11-14 17:18:17', '2010-11-14 17:18:17', '', 121, 'http://coffeebot.co/?p=245', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(402, 1, '2010-12-22 14:08:09', '2010-12-22 14:08:09', '<script src="http://connect.facebook.net/en_US/all.js#xfbml=1"></script><fb:like show_faces="true" width="450"></fb:like>\r\n<div id="rating-block">\r\n\r\n[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="4" cat1detail="Killer, well-crafted coffee" cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="3.5" cat2detail="Vibrant and unassuming"]\r\n<table id="info">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="title">Features <a title="key" href="http://localhost/coffeebot/?page_id=195">(Key)</a></td>\r\n<td><span class="food">Food</span><span class="free-parking">free parking</span><span class="wifi">WiFi</span><span class="manual">manual</span><span class="atm">ATM</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="address">2116 Pearl Street, Boulder, CO 80302 </td>\r\n<td class="phone">(303) 247-0124 </td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">“Espressoria” is in the name, why <em>wouldn''t</em> you go there?</span> I discovered this place while trying to go to another coffee shop that was completely packed. Bot1 has no patience for traffic or mobs of people, and when confronted with such situations, his programmed reaction is to drive 30 mph over the speed limit in one direction--stopping for no one. That''s even more dangerous considering the amount of college students and left-over hippies riding around on bicycles in this town. Had he not erupted in such acutely emulated anger, we would never have stumbled across Jet''s Espressoria—quaintly situated slightly off the beaten path in Boulder, Colorado.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee.</span> An Americano was ordered, and it was presented to me in a mug and with a beautiful golden crema. As I sipped it, my mouth was filled with a wonderful rich, dense, and full-bodied flavor. It was exactly what I needed after riding in a Subaru with a crazed robot. The flavor held, and over the course of my stay the taste never turned extremely acidic, like some coffees tend to do as they cool. This was the work of a fine roast, great espresso skills, and a wonderful espresso machine. Based on a tweet from back in July, they serve Box Car Espresso, Novo Espresso, and Boulder Organic Espresso. For any of you who have read my other posts, you know you usually have me at “Novo”. Judging from the extremely steady stream of customers, they all agreed with the quality as well. \r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere.</span> This place has a very local, neighborhood, some might say “indie” feel. I interpreted a loose 50''s vibe underscored by photographs of abandoned Route 66-style motels and gas stations, retro-looking tables and chairs and swirling ceiling fans. On the face of it, I personally am not a fan of this kind of look for a coffee shop, but I found myself quite comfortable and Bot1 felt he was among kin, being that most of his metal body work originated from the 50''s. It also had the dinge (which I''m beginning to think is a word I made up) factor I love so much: sketchy paint jobs, cluttered bar and counter, uneven tables and hand-written signs. It was also filled with the bicycle riding naturalists, designers, and college students that Bot1 nearly annihilated on the way over. In short, a great mix of people.\r\n\r\nJet''s Espressoria also bills itself as a bakery and their presentation of fine items was not lacking. Because of their $5 minimum for credit card use, I ordered a blueberry muffin as well. When I do these reviews I''m well aware that I am merely taking a snapshot of an overall experience and I allow quite a bit for less-than-great food, drink, or atmosphere, but this blueberry muffin was, well, not great. That said, I noticed most people going for their assortment of quiches and breakfast burritos which all looked wonderful, and next time I visit I will be digging in to one of these for sure. \r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The End.</span> Overall this place was a killer find. The coffee quality is way up there and I am very willing to overlook the muffin disappointment in light of the fine coffee and atmosphere. The employees (owners?) were very friendly and seemed genuinely focused on providing an outstanding product. Bring cash or buy lots of stuff since they have a $5 charge minimum, and try it! <span class="end-icon">END</span>\r\n[mappress mapid="7"]\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\r\n<hr />', 'Jet''s Espressoria', 'I discovered this place while trying to go to another coffee shop that was completely packed. Bot1 has no patience for traffic or mobs of people, and when confronted with such situations, his programmed reaction is to drive 30 mph over the speed limit in one direction--stopping for no one. That''s even more dangerous considering the amount of college students and left-over hippies riding around on bicycles in this town. Had he not erupted in such acutely emulated anger, we would never have stumbled across Jet''s Espressoria—quaintly situated slightly off the beaten path in Boulder, Colorado.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '333-revision-14', '', '', '2010-12-22 14:08:09', '2010-12-22 14:08:09', '', 333, 'http://coffeebot.co/uncategorized/333-revision-14/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(247, 1, '2010-11-14 17:19:42', '2010-11-14 17:19:42', '<p style="text-align: center;">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<div id="rating-block">\r\n\r\n[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="4.5" cat1detail="The focus is on the coffee here. Conversation, craftmanship and quality prove that point." cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="2" cat2detail="Tables were very uncomfortable and the overall decor left something to be desired. "]\r\n<table id="info">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="title">Features <a title="key" href="http://localhost/coffeebot/?page_id=195">(Key)</a></td>\r\n<td><span class="free-parking">Free parking</span><span class="wifi">WiFi</span><span class="manual">Manual Machine</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="address">7745 Wadsworth Boulevard, Arvada, CO 80003</td>\r\n<td class="phone">(303) 424-1313</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="website"><a title="Two Rivers Coffee" href="http://www.tworiverscoffee.com/">Website</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<span class="first-words">On a very hot day back in July</span> I came across Two Rivers Coffee. I stumbled in to the quiet, unassuming shop which promptly had me sold when I saw them using the Clover brewing system. Not only that, they served Novo Coffee, a gem in Colorado''s roasting belt. That said, it was hot, and I needed something cool.<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee</span> The person working there, who I later found out was the owner, convinced me to try what he called a "toddy", or a cold brewed coffee. I say convinced, because I am a pretty staunch hot coffee kind of guy. Bot1 couldn''t compute the concept of cold coffee, and already being overheated from the 90 degree outside temps, inadvertently went into hibernate mode before his processor overheated. However, I accepted. The cold brew turned out to be exactly what I needed on that hot day. Unlike other iced coffees that I''ve had which usually capitalize on overwhelmingly acidic, citrus notes to fool you in to thinking you''re being refreshed, there was a general lack of acidity which was replaced with a surprisingly deep, smooth palette of caramel and earth tones. Not at all what I expected from a cold coffee. A hint of spice lingered on my tongue and the aftertaste, despite the overall intensity, was very pleasant. The flavor lasted, as well, and despite being slightly watered down from the ice, my last sip was just as good as the first. I was sold.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere</span>As for the other important aspects to the shop: service and atmosphere, there are a few more notes to ad. Since I was served by the owner, I was immediately engaged in pleasant conversation and was able to talk for a fair amount of time about coffee, asking questions, etc., and he was more than willing to chat. I get the vibe that it''s an atmosphere he tries to foster. And, speaking of atmosphere, well, you don''t go there for it. The tables were uncomfortable, especially for the lengthy amount of time I was there (waiting on Bot1 to wake up), the blue walls made me nervous, and the local art display, while well-intentioned, was haphazard and not well organized.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The End</span><span style="color: #999999;"><em>(A note here: this original review was written back in July and I have since seen they are doing some work on the place, so the atmosphere complaint might be a moot point)</em></span> None of that would keep me from there, however, because this is the kind of coffee shop you go to for the superb coffee, you don''t have to go there for anything else. I strongly recommend you go and enjoy some of the highest quality coffee available here at 5,280 feet. <span class="end-icon">END</span>\r\n\r\n[mappress mapid="3"]', 'Two Rivers Coffee', 'On a very hot day back in July I came across Two Rivers Coffee. I stumbled in to the quiet, unassuming shop which promptly had me sold when I saw them using the Clover brewing system.That said, it was hot, and I needed something cool.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '52-revision-2', '', '', '2010-11-14 17:19:42', '2010-11-14 17:19:42', '', 52, 'http://coffeebot.co/?p=247', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
