eing a vital part of the community and being inspired by Italy''s espresso culture, yada yada yada. Nearly everyone says that. Even Howard Schultz said that at one time and look where that got us. However, their expressed desire to be a neighborhood coffee shop seems to actually be working.\r\n<h4><span class="first-words">The Coffee</span></h4>\r\nMy standard first-time drink is usually an Americano or latte. In this case, the Americano is a wonderful baseline drink. If made correctly, you get a lovely crema, the hot water and espresso combination even out the flavor of the coffee, and let''s face it: espresso is gone way too fast. I''m not Italian, for Pete''s sake. I love espresso shots but will only drink it straight in places I really trust. To my delight, I heard the familiar banging of portafilters into bins, and I had a feeling I was in for a treat. The drink was produced and brought to my table, whereupon I viewed that  nice layer of crema. The flavor was good. Not amazing, but good. The espresso certainly embodied everything a fine espresso should: full body, slight bitterness, subtle caramel tones; but for me, the dimension didn''t go far enough. That''s hardly a negative, since the intensity of espresso is, after all, subjective.\r\n<h4><span class="first-words">The Atmosphere</span></h4>\r\nFor once, this is a suburban coffee shop that is actually comfortable and has a hint of urban dinge that in my opinion, all the best coffee shops have. Sometimes, the dingier the better. The deep yellow-gold, black, copper and dark wood mix well to form a comfortable and inspiring atmosphere. Armed with a great comfy-couch area and plenty of tables (including outside seating) you definitely have your choice of places to sit. Mine, however, was by the fireplace. And that''s enough about the design, I drink coffee, after all.\r\n<h4><span class="first-words">The End</span></h4>\r\nFinally, the experience was punctuated by genuinely nice staff. I''ve been a few times, and even Bot1 has sneaked over there a couple times when I haven''t been looking. Witty small talk and a staff that calls  you by name on the second visit is a good step in the direction of having a lasting neighborhood coffee shop.<span class="end-icon">END</span>\r\n[mappress]', 'Forza Coffee', 'I was trying to decide which coffee house to review first for Coffee-Bot. Not the most easy decision to make considering here in the Denver metro area we have close to 10 x 8 to the third carry the two...coffee shops. OK, not that many, but still. Luckily, Bot1 made the decision for me, and it''s a good one: Forza Coffee in Westminster. I know, I know, a suburban coffee shop, but bear with me...', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '160-revision-4', '', '', '2010-11-14 17:43:59', '2010-11-14 17:43:59', '', 160, 'http://coffeebot.co/?p=255', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(401, 1, '2010-12-22 14:07:47', '2010-12-22 14:07:47', '<script src="http://connect.facebook.net/en_US/all.js#xfbml=1"></script><fb:like show_faces="true" width="450"></fb:like>\r\n<a href="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/illegal-grounds.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-365" title="illegal-grounds" src="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/illegal-grounds.jpg" alt="Illegal Grounds Coffee Shop" width="528" height="200" /></a>\r\n<div id="rating-block">[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="2.5" cat1detail="Utilitarian coffee: drinkable but nothing special." cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="3" cat2detail="Cozy living room feel but with a good amount of seating."]\r\n<table id="info">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="title">Features <a title="key" href="http://localhost/coffeebot/?page_id=195">(Key)</a></td>\r\n<td><span class="wifi">WiFi</span><span class="auto">Automatic Machine</span><span class="food">Pastries</span><span class="free-parking">Free street parking</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="address">925 East 17th Avenue, Denver, CO 80202</td>\r\n<td class="phone">(720) 434-0434</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="website">No website</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<span class="first-words">Bot1 insisted on Illegal Grounds in Denver''s Uptown neighborhood this time around.</span> He insisted because he is convinced anything with the word “Illegal” in it has to be awesome. If you remember back to his reading of “Death Beam” a few <a href="http://coffeebot.co/coffee-shop-reviews/common-grounds-coffee-house-3/">posts</a> ago, you know that I try to discourage anything that might be violent or illegal...or involve the word “death”. He may be a caffeine-converted robot, but there is no escaping what he was originally built for. However, I digress.\r\n\r\nIllegal Grounds, despite its name which implies a certain badness coupled with scary tattoos (or maybe the fact it was started by a lawyer?), is a very tame and inviting neighborhood coffee shop. Situated on the ground floor of an old Victorian house,  it embodies all the charms of a local favorite. Upon entrance, you walk straight down a hallway to the counter, and in my case, was met by a very friendly employee.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee.</span> An Americano was ordered and with it in hand, I turned the corner, entered the living room, and flopped down on one of the couches. Ultimately, I wasn''t going to expect much from the cup of coffee. The machine was automatic and they serve Illy coffee. Whenever I experience this kind of scenario, this usually translates to a very tame, albeit drinkable, cup of coffee. And I was right. There were no overwhelming flavors or distinctions to the espresso, just utilitarian goodness. I know I sound snooty when I immediately dismiss a beverage produced from an automatic machine, especially since this blog is called "Coffee Bot" which implies a certain level of automation, but understand that ultimately it is the human element in the creation of a beverage that gives it its ultimate dimension and uniqueness. It''s that human element that fuels my passion for exceptional coffee.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere.</span> The atmosphere didn''t disappoint. Once I rounded the corner into the seating area (or living room), I was immediately impressed with how many tables and chairs could fit amid the cozy space. A large picture window at the end of the room gave a bright, framed view of 17th street, and the light that poured in lit the walls full of local art. Wood floors, quiet music and a plentiful supply of power strips made Illegal Grounds a perfect spot to hunker down and get straight to conversation, work, or relaxation. <em>Take note: this place was pretty quiet despite the small crowd. To that end, if you are going to discuss the party habits of fellow world leaders and don''t want your secrets ending up on Wikileaks, this might not be the right place for those conversations. Alternatively, you could sit outside on the covered porch-there are far less people there. </em>\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The End.</span> Even though Bot1 didn''t fit easily between the tables and chairs, I would say our visit was a success and we will definitely return. The coffee gets the job done, the employees were very friendly,  and the atmosphere makes you want to hang around a little longer than you might at another coffee shop. <span class="end-icon">END</span>\r\n[mappress mapid="8"]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>', 'Illegal Grounds ', '<a href="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/illegal-grounds.jpg"><img src="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/illegal-grounds.jpg" alt="Illegal Grounds Coffee Shop" title="illegal-grounds" width="528" height="200" class="size-full wp-image-365" /></a>\r\nIllegal Grounds, despite its name which implies a certain badness coupled with scary tattoos (or maybe the fact it was started by a lawyer?), is a very tame and inviting neighborhood coffee shop. Situated on the ground floor of an old Victorian house,  it embodies all the charms of a local favorite. Upon entrance, you walk straight in down a hallway to the counter, and in my case, was met by a very friendly employee.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '364-revision-26', '', '', '2010-12-22 14:07:47', '2010-12-22 14:07:47', '', 364, 'http://coffeebot.co/uncategorized/364-revision-26/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(257, 1, '2010-11-14 17:57:32', '2010-11-14 17:57:32', '<p style="text-align: center;">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\n<p style="text-align: left;"></p>\n\n<hr /><a href="http://localhost/coffeebot/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/paris-platte.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-138" title="Paris On The Platte" src="http://localhost/coffeebot/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/paris-platte.jpg" alt="Paris On The Platte" width="530" height="200" /></a>\n\n<hr />\n<div id="rating-block">\n\n[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="3" cat1detail="Utilitarian caffeine with modest attention to quality." cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="3.5" cat2detail="Dark where it needs to be, light where it''s important, local art and aged/warehouse character"]\n<table id="info">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td class="title">Features <a title="key" href="http://localhost/coffeebot/?page_id=195">(Key)</a></td>\n<td><span class="alcohol">Alcohol</span><span class="food">Food</span><span class="paid-parking">Free parking</span><span class="wifi">WiFi</span><span class="manual">Manual Machine</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class="address">1553 Platte St, Denver, CO 80202</td>\n<td class="phone">(303) 455-2451</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class="website"><a title="Paris On The Platte" href="http://www.parisontheplattecafeandbar.com">Website</a></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</div>\n<span class="first-words">Paris on the Platte is one of my favorite urban coffee bars in the Denver metro.</span> It has all the great ''cool factors'': local art that is usually good, a store-front facing a lively street, weathered decor,  indie rock (I walked in to Viva Voce playing over the speakers—one of my favorite bands), citizens in skinny jeans, and decent espresso. It''s a great place being not only a coffee shop, but also a cafe and bar.\n\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee</span> Bot1 showed up in a pair of skinny jeans he had purchased from the Salvation Army, and after I wrestled them off of him, he sulked up to the counter and ordered a small latte. Even though we ordered a small, it came in a nice big mug, and after some detailed chemical analysis, Bot1 concluded the cinnamon on top of the foam was in fact, cinnamon. A nice touch, but if you don''t like people putting spices on your coffee, you might mention that upon ordering. After this, he lost interest, went over to the bar, and I was left to do the tasting by myself.\n\nThe latte was...good; nothing amazing. The foam was a tad bubbly and I would have liked more espresso presence, but the flavor that was there was smooth and balanced, so I can''t really complain. This isn''t an artisan place, so I didn''t detect much passion for coffee itself; I understand that coffee passion isn''t necessarily the point to the place.\n\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere</span> The main thing about this joint is that you can come in, set up your lappy, and do what you do best: hit up Facebook. Keep in mind that most people who sit there for a while are also on their laptops, so the connection speed is pretty slow. So, if you''re heading there to play Warcraft, it might not be the best place. Then again, you probably wouldn''t actually head outside to go to a coffee shop, either.\n\nAnother great aspect is the presence of living, breathing people (not just spoiled robots), and at this place, the flow of humans is pretty constant. Of all the times I have visited, I''ve never seen it empty, and I like that. The steady murmur of conversation is the perfect soundtrack to get my work done. It definitely is a neighborhood staple, and you aren''t without choices on where to sit or plug in. There''s plenty of room in the coffee side, bar side, and there''s even a little patio outback where cigarettes tend to be smoked.\n\n<span class="first-words">The End</span> Overall, it''s a good place, and I find myself recommending it often. Bot1 even likes it, but I can''t be sure the presence of wine next door is not swaying his judgment.<span class="end-icon">END</span>\n\n', 'Paris on the Platte Cafe &amp; Bar', 'Paris on the Platte is one of my favorite urban coffee bars in the Denver metro. It has all the great ''cool factors'': local art that is usually good, a store-front facing a busy, lively street, beaten-up decor,  indie rock (I walked in to Viva Voce playing-one of my fav''s), citizens in skinny jeans, and decent espresso. It''s a unique place being not only a coffee shop, but also a wine bar.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '121-autosave', '', '', '2010-11-14 17:57:32', '2010-11-14 17:57:32', '', 121, 'http://coffeebot.co/?p=257', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
