n likes it, but I can''t be sure the presence of wine next door is not swaying his judgment.<span class="end-icon">END</span>\r\n\r\n[mappress mapid="4"]', 'Paris on the Platte Cafe &amp; Bar', 'Paris on the Platte is one of my favorite urban coffee bars in the Denver metro. It has all the great ''cool factors'': local art that is usually good, a store-front facing a busy, lively street, beaten-up decor,  indie rock (I walked in to Viva Voce playing-one of my fav''s), citizens in skinny jeans, and decent espresso. It''s a unique place being not only a coffee shop, but also a wine bar.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '121-revision-4', '', '', '2010-11-14 17:50:28', '2010-11-14 17:50:28', '', 121, 'http://coffeebot.co/?p=258', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(259, 1, '2011-01-28 21:25:18', '2011-01-28 21:25:18', '<p style="text-align: center;">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\n\n<hr />\n<div id="rating-block">\n\n[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="4.5" cat1detail="The focus is on the coffee here. Conversation, craftmanship and quality prove that point." cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="2" cat2detail="Tables were very uncomfortable and the overall decor left something to be desired. "]\n<table id="info">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td class="title">Features <a title="key" href="http://www.coffeebot.co/?page_id=195">(Key)</a></td>\n<td><span class="no-atm">No ATM</span><span class="no-alcohol">No Alcohol</span><span class="no-music">No Music</span><span class="yes-parking">Free Parking</span><span class="no-food">No Food</span><span class="yes-wifi">Free Wifi</span><span class="manual">Manual Espresso Machine</span>\n</td>\n\n<td><span class="no-atm">No ATM</span><span class="no-alcohol">No Alcohol</span><span class="live-music">Live Music</span><span class="yes-parking">Free Parking</span><span class="yes-food">Food is Served</span><span class="yes-wifi">Free Wifi</span><span class="manual">Manual Espresso Machine</span>\n</td>\n\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class="address">7745 Wadsworth Boulevard, Arvada, CO 80003</td>\n<td class="phone">(303) 424-1313</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class="website"><a title="Two Rivers Coffee" href="http://www.tworiverscoffee.com/">Website</a></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</div>\n<span class="first-words">On a very hot day back in July</span> I came across Two Rivers Coffee. I stumbled in to the quiet, unassuming shop which promptly had me sold when I saw them using the Clover brewing system. Not only that, they served Novo Coffee, a gem in Colorado''s roasting crown. That said, it was hot, and I needed something cool.<!--more-->\n\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee</span> The person working there, who I later found out was the owner, convinced me to try what he called a "toddy", or a cold brewed coffee. I say convinced, because I am a pretty staunch hot coffee kind of guy. Bot1 couldn''t compute the concept of cold coffee, and already being overheated from the 90 degree outside temps, inadvertently went into hibernate mode before his processor overheated. However, I accepted. The cold brew turned out to be exactly what I needed on that hot day. Unlike other iced coffees that I''ve had which usually capitalize on overwhelmingly acidic, citrus notes to fool you in to thinking you''re being refreshed, there was a general lack of acidity which was replaced with a surprisingly deep, smooth palette of caramel and earth tones. Not at all what I expected from a cold coffee. A hint of spice lingered on my tongue and the aftertaste, despite the overall intensity, was very pleasant. The flavor lasted, as well, and despite being slightly watered down from the ice, my last sip was just as good as the first. I was sold.\n\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere</span>As for the other important aspects to the shop: service and atmosphere, there are a few more notes to ad. Since I was served by the owner, I was immediately engaged in pleasant conversation and was able to talk for a fair amount of time about coffee, asking questions, etc., and he was more than willing to chat. I get the vibe that it''s an atmosphere he tries to foster. And, speaking of atmosphere, well, you don''t go there for it. The tables were uncomfortable, especially for the lengthy amount of time I was there (waiting on Bot1 to wake up), the blue walls made me nervous, and the local art display, while well-intentioned, was haphazard and not well organized.\n\n<span class="first-words">The End</span><span style="color: #999999;"><em>(A note here: this original review was written back in July and I have since seen they are doing some work on the place, so the atmosphere complaint might be a moot point)</em></span> None of that would keep me from there, however, because this is the kind of coffee shop you go to for the superb coffee, you don''t have to go there for anything else. I strongly recommend you go and enjoy some of the highest quality coffee available here at 5,280 feet. <span class="end-icon">END</span>\n\n[mappress mapid="2"]', 'Two Rivers Coffee', 'On a very hot day back in July I came across Two Rivers Coffee. I stumbled in to the quiet, unassuming shop which promptly had me sold when I saw them using the Clover brewing system.That said, it was hot, and I needed something cool.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '52-autosave', '', '', '2011-01-28 21:25:18', '2011-01-28 21:25:18', '', 52, 'http://coffeebot.co/?p=259', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
