n the ground floor of an old Victorian house,  it embodies all the charms of a local favorite. Upon entrance, you walk straight in down a hallway to the counter, and in my case, was met by a very friendly employee.\r\n\r\nAn Americano was ordered and with it in hand, I turned the corner, entered the living room, and flopped down on one of the couches. Ultimately, I wasn''t going to expect much from the cup of coffee. The machine was automatic and they serve Illy coffee. Whenever I experience this kind of scenario, this usually translates to a very tame, albeit drinkable, cup of coffee. And I was right. There were no overwhelming flavors or distinctions to the espresso, just utilitarian goodness. I know, I sound snooty when I immediately dismiss a beverage produced from an automatic machine, especially since this blog is called Coffee Bot which implies a certain level of automation, but understand that ultimately it is the human element in the creation of a beverage that gives it its ultimate dimension and uniqueness. It''s that which fuels my passion for exceptional coffee.\r\n\r\nThe atmosphere didn''t disappoint. Once I rounded the corner into the seating area (or living room), I was immediately impressed with how many tables and chairs were fit amid the cozy space. A large picture window at the end of the room gave a bright, framed view of 17th street, and the light that poured in lit the walls full of local art. Wood floors, quiet music and a plentiful supply of power strips made Illegal Grounds a perfect spot to hunker down and get straight to conversation, work, or relaxation.  \r\n\r\nEven though Bot1 didn''t fit easily between the tables and chairs, I would say our visit was a success and we will definitely return. The coffee gets the job done, the employees were very friendly,  and the atmosphere makes you want to hang around a little longer than you might at another coffee shop. \r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</