(405, 2, '2010-12-31 17:44:17', '2010-12-31 17:44:17', '<script src="http://connect.facebook.net/en_US/all.js#xfbml=1"></script><fb:like show_faces="true" width="450"></fb:like>\r\n<div id="rating-block">\r\n[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="2.5" cat1detail="Utilitarian coffee: drinkable but nothing special." cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="2" cat2detail="Tidy and worn but friendly."]\r\n<table id="info">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="title">Features <a title="key" href="http://coffeebot.co/about-2/symbol-key/">(Key)</a></td>\r\n<td><span class="no-atm">No ATM</span><span class="no-alcohol">No Alcohol</span><span class="live-music">Live Music</span><span class="yes-parking">Free Parking</span><span class="yes-food">Food is Served</span><span class="yes-wifi">Free Wifi</span><span class="manual">Manual Espresso Machine</span>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="address">5756 Olde Wadsworth Blvd, Arvada, CO 80002</td>\r\n<td class="phone">(303) 456-8919</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="website"><a href="http://ladolcevitacoffee.wordpress.com/">Website</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">After browsing the local shops of Olde Town Arvada for spools of copper wire</span> (I didn’t ask), Bot1 and I decided to stop in La Dolce Vita for a restorative cuppa. On first impression, this shop appears tidy, but worn and outdated—rather like your kitschy great-aunt’s 80s-tastic pastel dining room. The marble and cast-iron tables, though, are wonderfully stable for writing, playing chess, etc. (I scoff at Bot2’s affinity for wobbly furniture). The place was almost awkwardly quiet, but we were glad that there were only a handful of other early afternoon customers because the single barista, though rather adept at latte art, operated the manual espresso machine fairly slowly. In dealing with customers—including our delightful selves and some who were more than a little obnoxious—she upheld La Dolce Vita’s claim of being “Arvada’s friendliest coffeehouse,” without seeming overly pushy or fake.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee.</span> La Dolce Vita offers a pretty extensive selection of teas, espresso, and syrup flavors, as well as breakfast items and pastries, but I settled on a small americano (12oz. = $2.20). The espresso was very mild and smooth—perfectly adequate for a quick boost after shopping, though not a lot to savor. This shop does run specials (e.g. $1.75 lattes after 2pm) and provides a loyalty card to allow regulars to earn a free drink, which is always a plus in my rather sparse pocketbook.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere. </span>There were plenty of tables inside (and a handful on the sidewalk outside), so we choose a semi-private spot in the bay window. The general lack of outlets in this area seemed to distress Bot1 on principle, but I appreciated that the laptop creeper who wanted to share our table had to sit across the room (I imagine he couldn’t help gravitating toward bots, though I’ve resolved to practice looking unsavory).\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The End.</span> If you go, a note of warning: there is a step from the café seating area down to the counter. For some reason, the glaring yellow signs warning me to watch my step proved difficult to read while I was falling on my face. In addition, La Dolce Vita plays host to a variety of local live music performances on most Saturdays, including the occasional “open mic night.” The music begins around 7pm, but if you want a seat, get there before the locals crowd in. <span class="end-icon">END</span>\r\n\r\n[mappress mapid="9"]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style="text-align: center">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>', 'La Dolce Vita', 'After browsing the local shops of Olde Town Arvada for spools of copper wire (I didn’t ask), Bot1 and I decided to stop in La Dolce Vita for a restorative cuppa. On first impression, this shop appears tidy, but worn and outdated—rather like your kitschy great-aunt’s 80s-tastic pastel dining room.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'la-dolce-vita', '', '', '2011-01-28 21:06:34', '2011-01-28 21:06:34', '', 0, 'http://coffeebot.co/?p=405', 0, 'post', '', 2),
(346, 1, '2010-12-06 02:26:56', '2010-12-06 02:26:56', 'Food, free wifi, ATM, Manual machine, free parking, \r\nCoffee – 4\r\nAtmosphere - 4\r\n\r\nJet''s Espressoria\r\n\r\nI actually discovered this place while trying to go to another coffee shop that was completely slammed. Bot1 has no patience for traffic or mobs of people, and when confronted with such a situation, his programmed reaction is to drive 30 mph over the speed limit in a single direction, stopping for no one. (Much like my father used to do, but I don''t see any real connection.) That''s even more dangerous considering the amount of college students and left-over hippies riding around on bicycles in this town. Had he not erupted in such acutely emulated anger, we never would have stumbled across Jet''s Espressoria—quaintly situated just off the beaten path in Boulder.\r\n\r\nThis place has a very local, neighborhood, some might say “indie” feel. There is a distinct kitschy 50''s feel punctuated with photographs of abandoned Route 66 style motels and gas stations, retro tables and chairs and swirling ceiling fans. On the face of it, I wouldn''t have thought that look would work well for a cozy shop, but I found myself quite comfortable and Bot1 felt among family being that most of his metal work originated from the 50''s. It also had the dinge (which I''m beginning to think is a word I made up) factor I love so much: fairly uneven floors, sketchy paint job, cluttered bar and counter, uneven tables and hand-written signs. It was also filled with the bicycle riding hippies and college students that Bot1 nearly annihilated. This is a mix that many of the more college-frequented joints don''t really have. \r\n\r\nThe coffee. An Americano was ordered, and it was presented to me in a mug and with a nice thick crema. As I sipped it, my mouth was filled with a  wonderful rich and full-bodied flavor. It was exactly what I needed after riding in a Subaru with a crazed robot. The flavor held, too, and over the course of my stay the flavor never turned extremely acidic, like some coffees tend to do. This was the work of a fine coffee, great espresso skills, and a wonderful machine. Judging from the extremely steady stream of customers, they agree with the quality as well. \r\n\r\nJet''s Espressoria also bills itself as a bakery and their presentation of fine items was not lacking. Because of their $5 minimum for credit card use, I ordered a blueberry muffin as well. When I do these reviews I''m well aware that I am merely taking a snapshot of an overall experience and I allow quite a bit for less-than-great food, drink, or atmosphere, but this blueberry muffin was horrible. What flavor it used to have had completely evaporated away leaving a dry memory of something once edible. I tried to finish it, but I couldn''t. That said, I noticed most people going for their assortment of quiches and breakfast burritos which all looked wonderful, and next time I visit I will be digging in to one of these for sure.\r\n\r\nOverall this place was a killer find. The coffee quality is way up there and I am super willing to overlook the muffin disappointment in light of the atmosphere and coffee. The employees were very friendly, and while quite focused on their job, didn''t make you feel unwelcome.  Try it!\r\n\r\n ', 'Jet''s Espressoria', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '333-revision-2', '', '', '2010-12-06 02:26:56', '2010-12-06 02:26:56', '', 333, 'http://coffeebot.co/uncategorized/333-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
