capitalize on overwhelmingly acidic, citrus notes to fool you in to thinking you''re being refreshed, there was a general lack of acidity which was replaced with a surprisingly deep, smooth palette of caramel and earth tones. Not at all what I expected from a cold coffee. A hint of spice lingered on my tongue and the aftertaste, despite the overall intensity, was very pleasant. The flavor lasted, as well, and despite being slightly watered down from the ice, my last sip was just as good as the first. I was sold.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere</span>As for the other important aspects to the shop: service and atmosphere, there are a few more notes to ad. Since I was served by the owner, I was immediately engaged in pleasant conversation and was able to talk for a fair amount of time about coffee, asking questions, etc., and he was more than willing to chat. I get the vibe that it''s an atmosphere he tries to foster. And, speaking of atmosphere, well, you don''t go there for it. The tables were uncomfortable, especially for the lengthy amount of time I was there (waiting on Bot1 to wake up), the blue walls made me nervous, and the local art display, while well-intentioned, was haphazard and not well organized.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The End</span><span style="color: #999999;"><em>(A note here: this original review was written back in July and I have since seen they are doing some work on the place, so the atmosphere complaint might be a moot point)</em></span> None of that would keep me from there, however, because this is the kind of coffee shop you go to for the superb coffee, you don''t have to go there for anything else. I strongly recommend you go and enjoy some of the highest quality coffee available here at 5,280 feet. <span class="end-icon">END</span>\r\n\r\n[mappress mapid="2"]', 'Two Rivers Coffee', 'On a very hot day back in July I came across Two Rivers Coffee. I stumbled in to the quiet, unassuming shop which promptly had me sold when I saw them using the Clover brewing system.That said, it was hot, and I needed something cool.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '52-revision-10', '', '', '2010-12-13 18:25:43', '2010-12-13 18:25:43', '', 52, 'http://coffeebot.co/uncategorized/52-revision-10/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(381, 1, '2010-12-20 20:33:35', '2010-12-20 20:33:35', '<script src="http://connect.facebook.net/en_US/all.js#xfbml=1"></script><fb:like show_faces="true" width="528”></fb:like>\n<div id="rating-block">\n\n<a href="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/illegal-grounds.jpg"><img src="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/illegal-grounds.jpg" alt="Illegal Grounds Coffee Shop" title="illegal-grounds" width="528" height="200" class="size-full wp-image-365" /></a>\n\n<div id="rating-block">\n[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="2.5" cat1detail="Utilitarian coffee: drinkable but nothing special." cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="3" cat2detail="Cozy living room feel but with a good amount of seating."]\n<table id="info">\n<tr>\n<td class="title">Features <a href="http://localhost/coffeebot/?page_id=195" title="key">(Key)</a></td>\n<td><span class="wifi">WiFi</span><span class="auto">Automatic Machine</span><span class="food">Pastries</span><span class="free-parking">Free street parking</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class="address">925 East 17th Avenue, Denver, CO 80202</td>\n<td class="phone">(720) 434-0434</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class="website">No website</td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n</div>\n\n<span class="first-words">Bot1 insisted on Illegal Grounds in Denver''s Uptown neighborhood this time around.</span> He insisted because he is convinced anything with the word “Illegal” in it has to be awesome. If you remember back to his reading of “Death Beam” a few posts ago, you know that I try to discourage anything that might be violent or illegal...or involve the word “death”. He may be a caffeine-converted robot, but there is no escaping what he was originally built for. However, I digress.\n\nIllegal Grounds, despite its name which implies a certain badness coupled with scary tattoos (or maybe the fact it was started by a lawyer?), is a very tame and inviting neighborhood coffee shop. Situated on the ground floor of an old Victorian house,  it embodies all the charms of a local favorite. Upon entrance, you walk straight down a hallway to the counter, and in my case, was met by a very friendly employee.\n\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee.</span> An Americano was ordered and with it in hand, I turned the corner, entered the living room, and flopped down on one of the couches. Ultimately, I wasn''t going to expect much from the cup of coffee. The machine was automatic and they serve Illy coffee. Whenever I experience this kind of scenario, this usually translates to a very tame, albeit drinkable, cup of coffee. And I was right. There were no overwhelming flavors or distinctions to the espresso, just utilitarian goodness. I know I sound snooty when I immediately dismiss a beverage produced from an automatic machine, especially since this blog is called "Coffee Bot" which implies a certain level of automation, but understand that ultimately it is the human element in the creation of a beverage that gives it its ultimate dimension and uniqueness. It''s that human element that fuels my passion for exceptional coffee.\n\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere.</span> The atmosphere didn''t disappoint. Once I rounded the corner into the seating area (or living room), I was immediately impressed with how many tables and chairs could fit amid the cozy space. A large picture window at the end of the room gave a bright, framed view of 17th street, and the light that poured in lit the walls full of local art. Wood floors, quiet music and a plentiful supply of power strips made Illegal Grounds a perfect spot to hunker down and get straight to conversation, work, or relaxation. <em>Take note: this place was pretty quiet despite the small crowd. To that end, if you are going to discuss the party habits of fellow world leaders and don''t want your secrets ending up on Wikileaks, this might not be the right place for those conversations. Alternatively, you could sit outside on the covered porch-there are far less people there. </em>\n\n<span class="first-words">The End.</span> Even though Bot1 didn''t fit easily between the tables and chairs, I would say our visit was a success and we will definitely return. The coffee gets the job done, the employees were very friendly,  and the atmosphere makes you want to hang around a little longer than you might at another coffee shop. \n[mappress mapid="8"]\n<hr />\n<p style="text-align: center;">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\n<hr />', 'Illegal Grounds ', '<a href="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/illegal-grounds.jpg"><img src="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/illegal-grounds.jpg" alt="Illegal Grounds Coffee Shop" title="illegal-grounds" width="528" height="200" class="size-full wp-image-365" /></a>\nIllegal Grounds, despite its name which implies a certain badness coupled with scary tattoos (or maybe the fact it was started by a lawyer?), is a very tame and inviting neighborhood coffee shop. Situated on the ground floor of an old Victorian house,  it embodies all the charms of a local favorite. Upon entrance, you walk straight in down a hallway to the counter, and in my case, was met by a very friendly employee.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '364-revision-16', '', '', '2010-12-20 20:33:35', '2010-12-20 20:33:35', '', 364, 'http://coffeebot.co/uncategorized/364-revision-16/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
