(384, 1, '2010-12-13 18:22:26', '2010-12-13 18:22:26', '<p style="text-align: center;">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<a href="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/common-grounds.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-286" title="common-grounds" src="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/common-grounds.jpg" alt="common grounds coffee house" width="528" height="200" /></a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\r\n\r\n<div id="rating-block">\r\n\r\n[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="2.5" cat1detail="Care is taken in preparation, but overall espresso quality seems to be lacking." cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="3.5" cat2detail="Lot''s of seating, power outlets, local art, bright and natural light."]\r\n<table id="info">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="title">Features <a title="key" href="http://localhost/coffeebot/?page_id=195">(Key)</a></td>\r\n<td><span class="alcohol">alcohol</span><span class="food">Food</span><span class="paid-parking">paid and street parking</span><span class="wifi">WiFi</span><span class="manual">manual</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="address">1550 17th Street, Denver (LoDo Location)</td>\r\n<td class="phone">(303) 296-9248</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="website"><a title="Common Grounds Coffee House" href="http://www.commongroundscoffeehouse.com/">Website</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<span class="first-words">It was a quiet day. A little bored, Bot1 insisted we consult my very-cute-coffee-name-pun list</span> to see if something piqued our interest, and it was then we decided on Common Grounds Coffee House. <a href="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/deathbeam.jpg"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-308" title="deathbeam" src="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/deathbeam.jpg" alt="deathbeam" width="250" height="188" /></a>While usually passionate about the coffee (passion being one of Bot1''s few emulated emotions), Bot1 was more interested in reading “Death Beam”, a title he''d spotted on the bookshelf, and while I always try to discourage him reading anything with “death” in it, I decided to pick my battle and allow it. Bot1 then marched up to the counter, emitted his demand for a whole milk latte and a double espresso, beamed the book off the shelf, and proceeded to process the pages via his OCR scanner.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee.</span> As usual, I was left with the coffee. The person who made the drinks was extremely friendly (bonus) and after a pleasant interaction about the weather she proceeded to focus in on the latte. I noticed she took much care when steaming the milk and while I couldn''t see the shots as they were extracted, the aroma was enticing and the shots were swiftly combined with the milk. I was given the latte which embodied thick, dense foam, slight hints of brown espresso swirled through the mix, and a warmth that was comforting on that chilly day. Ultimately, however, the flavor, while it didn''t disappoint, was only average. To be certain, it was a good latte—one I would return for—but  once again the reality was that to have truly impressive beverages, the coffee itself must be spectacular, and it just wasn''t. The double espresso disappointed slightly as well. The crema was thin and nearly immediately broke to reveal the dark body of the shot. The“raining” effect or separation of the shot was reminiscent of Guinness, which, as luck would have it, is served at Common Grounds as well. The flavor didn''t go deep enough either. The initial stark bitterness never really left my tongue and the acidity was slightly overwhelming, so much so that any dimension that might have been there was masked by this intensity.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere.</span> Common Grounds embodied a balanced mix of the old and new. The counter and bar were your typical curvy-bistro-coolness with lots of angles thrown in that made for exciting visuals. There was plenty of room to sprawl out on one of their two very large tables, or keep to yourself on any one of their abundant four-seaters. One feature Bot1 and I liked a lot was the presence of bookshelves with actual physical books. On top of that, if one so desired, one could pick up and read...one. During my visit I did notice a young guy in skinny pants with his Mac under his arm stroking his chin in silent wonder at the spectacle of these books, but for the most part people knew what to do with them. Large windows overlooking the busy street allowed generous amounts of light in, illuminating the local art canvases aiding in a vibrant feel; and the constant murmur of machines, music, and conversation were all at the perfect level.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The End.</span> Common Grounds Coffee House withstands the test. Sure, I wasn''t bowled over by the coffee, but in the end it was <em>good</em>. Combined with the atmosphere and friendliness of the employees, it''s definitely a place you should check out. Bot1 agrees and also informed me “Death Beam” didn''t live up to his planet domination aspirations...much to my relief.<span class="end-icon">END</span>\r\n\r\n[mappress mapid="4"]<!--more-->', 'Common Grounds Coffee House', 'It was a quiet day. A little bored, Bot1 insisted we consult my very-cute-coffee-name-pun list to see if something piqued our interest, and it was then we decided on Common Grounds Coffee House. While usually passionate about the coffee (passion being one of Bot1''s few emulated emotions), Bot1 was more interested in reading “Death Beam”, a title he''d spotted on the bookshelf, and while I always try to discourage him reading anything with “death” in it', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '301-revision-14', '', '', '2010-12-13 18:22:26', '2010-12-13 18:22:26', '', 301, 'http://coffeebot.co/uncategorized/301-revision-14/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
