(471, 1, '2011-01-09 16:41:01', '2011-01-09 16:41:01', 'I recently discovered Google''s Ngram Viewer and found it really fascinating. For those of you who haven''t experienced the sheer excitement of this sort of thing, I''ll briefly explain: Google has digitized millions of books and made every word of them search-able, so when you type in a certain word, you can see how often that word has shown up in literature through the course of history. Of course, after punching in all the usual suspects: war, peace; male, female; Coke, Pepsi; I punched in coffee and tea. The graph acted a little like I thought it might with tea being fairly dominant for most of history. Both examples rise with the spread of literature and books for the people, but I noticed the rise and fall of these words seem to coincide with fairly big historical events. Anyone remember the Boston Tea Party? I am curious then, what other big coffee and tea historical events might be reflected on the graph? For those of you who are A) more knowledgeable of history than I am, and B) more knowledgeable of coffee than I am, I''d love to read what you think. And hop over to Google''s Ngram site, it''s a lot of fun!\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_472" align="alignleft" width="300" caption="Coffee and Tea Ngram from 1600 to now"]<a href="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/ngram-1600-now.jpg"><img src="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/ngram-1600-now-300x190.jpg" alt="Ngram from 1600 to now" title="ngram-1600-now" width="300" height="190" class="size-medium wp-image-472" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\n[caption id="attachment_476" align="alignleft" width="300" caption="Ngram of Coffee & Tea in the 20th century"]<a href="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/ngram-20th-century1.jpg"><img src="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/ngram-20th-century1-300x190.jpg" alt="Ngram 20th century" title="ngram-20th-century" width="300" height="190" class="size-medium wp-image-476" /></a>[/caption]\r\n', 'Coffee & Tea, War & Peace', 'I recently discovered Google''s Ngram Viewer and found it really fascinating. For those of you who haven''t experienced the sheer excitement of this sort of thing, I''ll briefly explain: Google has digitized millions of books and made every word of them search-able, so when you type in a certain word, you can see how often that word has shown up in literature through the course of history. Of course, after punching in all the usual suspects: war, peace; male, female; Coke, Pepsi; I punched in coffee and tea. ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'coffee-tea-war-peace', '', '', '2011-01-09 16:41:01', '2011-01-09 16:41:01', '', 0, 'http://coffeebot.co/?p=471', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(411, 1, '2010-12-30 20:13:09', '2010-12-30 20:13:09', 'After browsing the local shops of Olde Town Arvada for spools of copper wire (I didn’t ask), Bot1 and I decided to stop in La Dolce Vita for a restorative cuppa. On first impression, this shop appears tidy, but worn and outdated—rather like your kitschy great-aunt’s 80s-tastic pastel dining room. The marble and cast-iron tables, though, are wonderfully stable for writing, playing chess, etc. (I scoff at Bot2’s affinity for wobbly furniture). The place was almost awkwardly quiet, but we were glad that there were only a handful of other early afternoon customers because the single barista, though rather adept at latte art, operated the manual espresso machine fairly slowly. In dealing with customers—including our delightful selves and some who were more than a little obnoxious—she upheld La Dolce Vita’s claim of being “Arvada’s friendliest coffeehouse,” without seeming overly pushy or fake.\r\n	La Dolce Vita offers a pretty extensive selection of teas, espresso, and syrup flavors, as well as breakfast items and pastries, but I settled on a small americano (12oz. = $2.20). The espresso was very mild and smooth—perfectly adequate for a quick boost after shopping, though not a lot to savor. This shop does run specials (e.g. $1.75 lattes after 2pm) and provides a loyalty card to allow regulars to earn a free drink, which is always a plus in my rather sparse pocketbook. \r\n	There were plenty of tables inside (and a handful on the sidewalk outside), so we choose a semi-private spot in the bay window. The general lack of outlets in this area seemed to distress Bot1 on principle, but I appreciated that the laptop creeper who wanted to share our table had to sit across the room (I imagine he couldn’t help gravitating toward bots, though I’ve resolved to practice looking unsavory).\r\n	If you go, a note of warning: there is a step from the café seating area down to the counter. For some reason, the glaring yellow signs warning me to watch my step proved difficult to read while I was falling on my face. In addition, La Dolce Vita plays host to a variety of local live music performances on most Saturdays, including the occasional “open mic night.” The music begins around 7pm, but if you want a seat, get there before the locals crowd in.', 'La Dolce Vita', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '405-revision-2', '', '', '2010-12-30 20:13:09', '2010-12-30 20:13:09', '', 405, 'http://coffeebot.co/uncategorized/405-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
