etty extensive selection of teas, espresso, and syrup flavors, as well as breakfast items and pastries, but I settled on a small americano (12oz. = $2.20). The espresso was very mild and smooth—perfectly adequate for a quick boost after shopping, though not a lot to savor. This shop does run specials (e.g. $1.75 lattes after 2pm) and provides a loyalty card to allow regulars to earn a free drink, which is always a plus in my rather sparse pocketbook.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere. </span>There were plenty of tables inside (and a handful on the sidewalk outside), so we choose a semi-private spot in the bay window. The general lack of outlets in this area seemed to distress Bot1 on principle, but I appreciated that the laptop creeper who wanted to share our table had to sit across the room (I imagine he couldn’t help gravitating toward bots, though I’ve resolved to practice looking unsavory).\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The End.</span> If you go, a note of warning: there is a step from the café seating area down to the counter. For some reason, the glaring yellow signs warning me to watch my step proved difficult to read while I was falling on my face. In addition, La Dolce Vita plays host to a variety of local live music performances on most Saturdays, including the occasional “open mic night.” The music begins around 7pm, but if you want a seat, get there before the locals crowd in. <span class="end-icon">END</span>\r\n\r\n[mappress mapid="9"]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style="text-align: center">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>', 'La Dolce Vita', 'After browsing the local shops of Olde Town Arvada for spools of copper wire (I didn’t ask), Bot1 and I decided to stop in La Dolce Vita for a restorative cuppa. On first impression, this shop appears tidy, but worn and outdated—rather like your kitschy great-aunt’s 80s-tastic pastel dining room.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '405-revision-20', '', '', '2010-12-31 17:31:23', '2010-12-31 17:31:23', '', 40