 caramel. It''s the equivalent to restoring peace to the world by neutralizing one coffee-assassinating flavor at a time. However, other than the occasional mocha, I don''t flavor my coffee, therefore my Americano was ordered. The lever was pulled, the shots were extracted, and the drink slid across the counter to me. The liquid rocked easily back and forth in the ceramic with the thick crema surface holding together tightly reflecting deep, red-brown and golden swirls. It glistened with the oily coffee bean residue (crema is the only time ''oil'' and ''residue'' are good things as descriptors), hinting at the flavor that was to come. Butter, caramel, slight smokiness, crisp acidity and a subtly bitter, the deep body filled my taste buds and for the first time in a very long time, I savored every single ounce of that Americano. It''s at this point I should mention the espresso was a Novo roast. Sound familiar? Other roasters who make an appearance at Crema are Herkimer and Pablo''s- according to the website, that is.\r\n\r\n<span class=”first-words”>The Atmosphere</span> is what it is. Clearly underground, it is cold, utilitarian, industrial and full of reclaimed odds and ends. The tables and chairs have that certain retro flair, and I''m pretty sure they are original stuff, not overpriced re-makes. Hip below-ground art adorned the brick/plaster walls when I first visited, and the room was quite bright thanks to a fairly large red-pained window in the front. I had a bit of trouble finding an outlet for my laptop and finally found one stuck around behind a couch, but I noticed plenty of people on their Macs not bothered by this lack who apparently have risen above the need for a plug. This is the sort of place you go to sip your velvety microfoam and discuss bands that don''t exist yet, not necessarily type up your doctoral thesis. There is a tiny bar that you can belly up to and watch the Baristas fashion their creations, and overall, considering the square footage, there is a good amount of seating for the size.\r\n\r\nFinally, a few points to note: First, you don''t go there if you are in a rush. It''s obvious the owner is more interested in the beverage quality than in the fact you forgot to set your alarm, spent too much time watching Regis and Kelly and are now running late for work. Every drink is made one-at-a time which maximizes quality but not speediness. In fact, if you are ordering a latte or cappuccino, every drink will also include some latte art, even if you are slapping a lid on it. Also Crema''s muffins are insanely good and as a bonus they don''t have the paper wrapper around the bottom so you don''t have to peel it off. Let me tell you, this is reason enough to go there! Finally, they have a great selection of fine teas, but that review is up to TeaBot, not me. \r\n\r\n<span class=”first-words”>The End</span> In conclusion: go there. No excuses, just go. You won''t regret it. ', 'Crema', '<a href="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/crema-5-star.jpg"><img src="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/crema-5-star.jpg" alt="" title="crema-5-star" width="528" height="200" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-438" /></a>', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '407-revision-8', '', '', '2011-01-04 23:11:56', '2011-01-04 23:11:56', '', 407, 'http://coffeebot.co/uncategorized/407-revision-8/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
