(481, 1, '2011-01-28 21:48:35', '2011-01-28 21:48:35', '<script src="http://connect.facebook.net/en_US/all.js#xfbml=1"></script><fb:like show_faces="true" width="450"></fb:like>\r\n<a href="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/pauls.jpg"><img src="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/pauls.jpg" alt="Paul&#039;s Coffee &amp; Tea" title="Paul&#039;s Coffee &amp; Tea" width="525" height="199" class="size-full wp-image-485" /></a>\r\n<div id="rating-block">\r\n[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="3.5" cat1detail="Coffee roasted on the spot makes for a good cup" cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="2.5" cat2detail="Pleasant, ''folky'' and bright "]\r\n<table id="info">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="title">Features <a title="key" href="http://coffeebot.co/about-2/symbol-key/">(Key)</a></td>\r\n<td><span class="no-atm">No ATM</span><span class="no-alcohol">No Alcohol</span><span class="live-music">Live Music</span><span class="yes-parking">Free Parking</span><span class="yes-food">Food is Served</span><span class="yes-wifi">Free Wifi</span><span class="manual">Manual Espresso Machine</span>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="address">956 West Cherry, Louisville, CO 80027</td>\r\n<td class="phone">(720) 259-1723</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="website"><a href="http://paulscoffeeandtea.com">Website</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">Bot1 and I arrived at Paul''s Coffee and Tea,</span> a modest coffee shop located in the commercial and professional area of Louisville, Colorado. Since Louisville consistently ranks in the top places to live in the US year after year (<a href="(http://money.cnn.com/magazines/moneymag/bplive/2009/snapshots/PL0846355.html)">Proof</a>), you expect its businesses to perform to a somewhat higher standard. Ultimately, this place does. True to the culture of the area, all the coffee served and roasted is fair trade and organic, caters to hippies and yuppies alike, has a very friendly staff, and owns its fair share of potted plants. Paul''s is definitely a place worth stopping in, and the added incentive for me is the fact they roast their own coffee. The roaster, positioned [strategically] close to the front door, greets you with the smokey-sweet aroma of roasted beans, an aroma that you hit like a wall upon entrance. \r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee.</span> True to form, a double espresso was ordered and Bot1 set to processing the menu''s unique price points (2.77 for a latte, for instance). At the first sip I was happy to taste a wonderfully balanced extraction with slight berry notes and a clean acidity. Translated, it was good. Bot1, who''d ordered a Mocha, let me share a bit of his which was also very good. He quickly snatched it back, however, since whipped cream offers one of the few excitements he gets to experience in his emulated life. This means the espresso holds its own <em>on</em> its own, or as the foundation to the assortment of espresso-based drinks. \r\n<a href="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/pauls-2.jpg"><img src="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/pauls-2.jpg" alt="Paul&#039;s Atmosphere" title="pauls-2" width="525" height="199" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-529" /></a>\r\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere.</span> The atmosphere draws you in with its simplicity folky charm. The entire east, north, and west walls are actually windows which offer peeks toward the Flatirons and rich sunlight that''s very warm in the winter but slightly too warm in the summer. The folk theme carries through with bluegrass instruments, country nick knacks, decrepit windows as wall art, and even a moonshine jug that Bot1 was entirely convinced was full of moonshine. It''s the sort of place you''d expect to find tucked back in the pines of the Rockies. Local art rotates fairly often and is always a good variety. There is a decent amount of tables and chairs and along the windows are a few power strips to plug your lifestyle in to. Be prepared to share a table with someone if you absolutely need an outlet though, since there isn''t a huge selection of tables along the windows. \r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The End.</span> With daily specials, customer loyalty punch cards, coffee by the press, happy hour, decent prices (even if they are a bit odd), perks if you donate to a charity and Saturday Bluegrass concerts, Paul''s definitely gives you plenty of reasons to return and get in touch with your country-coffee side. <span class="end-icon">END</span>\r\n[mappress mapid="11"]\r\n<br />\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\r\n<h2>Have you been to Paul''s Coffee & Tea? Share your experience in a comment below!</h2>', 'Paul''s Coffee & Tea', '<a href="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/pauls.jpg"><img src="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/pauls.jpg" alt="Paul&#039;s Coffee &amp; Tea" title="Paul&#039;s Coffee &amp; Tea" width="525" height="199" class="size-full wp-image-485" /></a>\r\nTrue to the culture of the area, all the coffee served and roasted is fair trade and organic, caters to hippies and yuppies alike, has a very friendly staff, and owns its fair share of potted plants. Paul''s is definitely a place worth stopping in, and the added incentive for me is the fact they roast their own coffee.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'pauls-coffee-tea', '', '', '2011-01-28 22:46:42', '2011-01-28 22:46:42', '', 0, 'http://coffeebot.co/?p=481', 0, 'post', '', 1),
