(514, 1, '2011-01-05 17:59:37', '2011-01-05 17:59:37', '<script src="http://connect.facebook.net/en_US/all.js#xfbml=1"></script><fb:like show_faces="true" width="450"></fb:like>\r\n<a href="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/crema.jpg"><img src="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/crema.jpg" alt="" title="crema" width="528" height="200" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-436" /></a>\r\n<div id="rating-block">\r\n[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="5" cat1detail="5 stars not given lightly, the proof is in the cup." cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="3.5" cat2detail="Underground and industrial."]\r\n<table id="info">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="title">Features <a title="key" href="http://coffeebot.co/about-2/symbol-key/">(Key)</a></td>\r\n<td><span class="wifi">WiFi</span><span class="manual">Manual Machine</span><span class="free-parking">Free Parking</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="address">2862 Larimer, Denver, CO 80205</td>\r\n<td class="phone">(720) 235-2995</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="website"><a href="http://cremacoffeehouse.net/">Website</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<span class="first-words">Prelude.</span> For those of you who have read my previous reviews, you may have noticed that when ever I am describing the coffee, I almost always remark on the crema. I do this because the crema is the soul of the espresso. Without it you are simply confronted with a dark and formless beverage that leaves you hovering over the face of some sort of liquid void. Crema contains the flavorful, complex, and oily soul of the espresso shot. It''s the lifeblood and excitement of coffee itself. \r\n\r\nThat said, when Bot1 discovered an entire coffee shop named after this beauty, it was a no-brainer, or in Bot1''s case, a no-CPUer that we check it out. Everything this shop does, it does well. The website, branding, interior design and ultimately, the coffee are nothing short of stellar. Bot1 is programmed to respond to excellence by demanding we go back again, and again, and again since it triggers an infinite system loop. Right off the bat, I''d recommend you do the same. \r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee.</span> As we entered Crema (nestled in the Five Points area, or NoDo) I was struck by the overall simplicity and itty-bitty-ness of the place. The counter is no more than four paces from the front door and the menu is purposefully sparse—not only in its lack of fluff beverages but also in the fact that it is printed on the wall. It was immediately apparent the owner is a purist. For instance, this is not the shop for suburban frappu-whatever drinkers. Crema offers only three flavors: mocha, vanilla and caramel. It''s the equivalent to restoring peace to the world by neutralizing one coffee-assassinating flavor at a time. However, other than the occasional mocha, I don''t flavor my coffee, therefore my Americano was ordered. The lever was pulled, the shots were extracted, and the drink slid across the counter to me. The liquid rocked easily back and forth in the ceramic with the thick crema surface holding together tightly reflecting deep, red-brown and golden swirls. It glistened with the oily coffee bean residue (crema is the only time ''oil'' and ''residue'' are good things as descriptors), hinting at the flavor that was to come. Butter, caramel, crisp acidity and subtle bitterness filled my taste buds and for the first time in a very long time, I savored every single ounce of that Americano. (It''s at this point I should mention the espresso was a Novo roast. Sound familiar? Other roasters who make an appearance at Crema are Herkimer and Pablo''s- according to the website, that is.)\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere</span> is what it is. Clearly underground, it is cold, utilitarian and industrial with a few reclaimed odds and ends. The tables and chairs have that certain retro flair, and I''m pretty sure they are original stuff, not overpriced re-makes. Hip below-ground art adorned the brick/plaster walls when I first visited, and the room was quite bright thanks to a fairly large red-pained window in the front. I had a bit of trouble finding an outlet for my laptop and finally found one behind a couch, but I noticed plenty of people on their Macs not bothered by this who apparently have risen above the need for a plug. Who needs an outlet, though? This is the sort of place you go to sip your velvety microfoam and discuss bands that don''t exist yet, not necessarily type up your doctoral thesis. There is a tiny bar that you can belly up to and watch the Baristas fashion their creations, and overall, considering the square footage, there is a good amount of seating for the size.\r\n\r\nFinally, a few points to note: First, you don''t go there if you are in a rush. It''s obvious the owner is more interested in the beverage quality than in the fact you forgot to set your alarm, spent too much time watching Kardashians reruns and are now running late for work. Every drink is made one-at-a time which maximizes quality but not speediness. In fact, if you are ordering a latte or cappuccino, each will include some sort of latte design, even if you are slapping a lid on it. Second, Crema''s muffins are insanely good and as a bonus they don''t have the paper wrapper around the bottom so you don''t have to peel it off. Let me tell you, this is reason enough to go there! Finally, they have a great selection of fine teas, but that review is up to TeaBot, not me, and TeaBot doesn''t even exist...yet.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The End</span> In conclusion: go there. No excuses, just go. You won''t regret it. \r\n[mappress mapid="10"]\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style="text-align: center">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\r\n<h2>Have you been to Crema? Share your experience in a comment below!</h2>', 'Crema Coffee House', '<a href="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/crema-5-star.jpg"><img src="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/crema-5-star.jpg" alt="" title="crema-5-star" width="528" height="200" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-438" /></a>\r\nWhen Bot1 discovered an entire coffee shop named after this beauty, it was a no-brainer, or in Bot1''s case, a no-CPUer that we check it out. Everything this shop does, it does well. The website, branding, interior design and ultimately, the coffee are nothing short of stellar. Bot1 is programmed to respond to excellence by demanding we go back again, and again, and again since it triggers an infinite system loop. Right off the bat, I''d recommend you do the same. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '407-revision-35', '', '', '2011-01-05 17:59:37', '2011-01-05 17:59:37', '', 407, 'http://coffeebot.co/coffee-shop-reviews/407-revision-35/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(515, 1, '2010-12-31 17:44:17', '2010-12-31 17:44:17', '<script src="http://connect.facebook.net/en_US/all.js#xfbml=1"></script><fb:like show_faces="true" width="450"></fb:like>\r\n<div id="rating-block">\r\n[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="2.5" cat1detail="Utilitarian coffee: drinkable but nothing special." cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="2" cat2detail="Tidy and worn but friendly."]\r\n<table id="info">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="title">Features <a title="key" href="http://coffeebot.co/about-2/symbol-key/">(Key)</a></td>\r\n<td><span class="wifi">WiFi</span><span class="manual">Manual Machine</span><span class="food">Food and Pastries</span><span class="free-parking">Free Parking</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="address">5756 Olde Wadsworth Blvd, Arvada, CO 80002</td>\r\n<td class="phone">(303) 456-8919</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="website"><a href="http://ladolcevitacoffee.wordpress.com/">Website</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">After browsing the local shops of Olde Town Arvada for spools of copper wire</span> (I didn’t ask), Bot1 and I decided to stop in La Dolce Vita for a restorative cuppa. On first impression, this shop appears tidy, but worn and outdated—rather like your kitschy great-aunt’s 80s-tastic pastel dining room. The marble and cast-iron tables, though, are wonderfully stable for writing, playing chess, etc. (I scoff at Bot2’s affinity for wobbly furniture). The place was almost awkwardly quiet, but we were glad that there were only a handful of other early afternoon customers because the single barista, though rather adept at latte art, operated the manual espresso machine fairly slowly. In dealing with customers—including our delightful selves and some who were more than a little obnoxious—she upheld La Dolce Vita’s claim of being “Arvada’s friendliest coffeehouse,” without seeming overly pushy or fake.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee.</span> La Dolce Vita offers a pretty extensive selection of teas, espresso, and syrup flavors, as well as breakfast items and pastries, but I settled on a small americano (12oz. = $2.20). The espresso was very mild and smooth—perfectly adequate for a quick boost after shopping, though not a lot to savor. This shop does run specials (e.g. $1.75 lattes after 2pm) and provides a loyalty card to allow regulars to earn a free drink, which is always a plus in my rather sparse pocketbook.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere. </span>There were plenty of tables inside (and a handful on the sidewalk outside), so we choose a semi-private spot in the bay window. The general lack of outlets in this area seemed to distress Bot1 on principle, but I appreciated that the laptop creeper who wanted to share our table had to sit across the room (I imagine he couldn’t help gravitating toward bots, though I’ve resolved to practice looking unsavory).\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The End.</span> If you go, a note of warning: there is a step from the café seating area down to the counter. For some reason, the glaring yellow signs warning me to watch my step proved difficult to read while I was falling on my face. In addition, La Dolce Vita plays host to a variety of local live music performances on most Saturdays, including the occasional “open mic night.” The music begins around 7pm, but if you want a seat, get there before the locals crowd in. <span class="end-icon">END</span>\r\n\r\n[mappress mapid="9"]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style="text-align: center">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>', 'La Dolce Vita', 'After browsing the local shops of Olde Town Arvada for spools of copper wire (I didn’t ask), Bot1 and I decided to stop in La Dolce Vita for a restorative cuppa. On first impression, this shop appears tidy, but worn and outdated—rather like your kitschy great-aunt’s 80s-tastic pastel dining room.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '405-revision-27', '', '', '2010-12-31 17:44:17', '2010-12-31 17:44:17', '', 405, 'http://coffeebot.co/coffee-shop-reviews/405-revision-27/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(516, 1, '2010-12-30 18:18:11', '2010-12-30 18:18:11', '<script src="http://connect.facebook.net/en_US/all.js#xfbml=1"></script><fb:like show_faces="true" width="450"></fb:like>\r\n<a href="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/illegal-grounds.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-365" title="illegal-grounds" src="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/illegal-grounds.jpg" alt="Illegal Grounds Coffee Shop" width="528" height="200" /></a>\r\n<div id="rating-block">[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="2.5" cat1detail="Utilitarian coffee: drinkable but nothing special." cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="3" cat2detail="Cozy living room feel but with a good amount of seating."]\r\n<table id="info">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="title">Features <a title="key" href="http://coffeebot.co/about-2/symbol-key/">(Key)</a></td>\r\n<td><span class="wifi">WiFi</span><span class="auto">Automatic Machine</span><span class="food">Pastries</span><span class="free-parking">Free street parking</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="address">925 East 17th Avenue, Denver, CO 80202</td>\r\n<td class="phone">(720) 434-0434</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="website">No website</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<span class="first-words">Bot1 insisted on Illegal Grounds in Denver''s Uptown neighborhood this time around.</span> He insisted because he is convinced anything with the word “Illegal” in it has to be awesome. If you remember back to his reading of “Death Beam” a few <a href="http://coffeebot.co/coffee-shop-reviews/common-grounds-coffee-house-3/">posts</a> ago, you know that I try to discourage anything that might be violent or illegal...or involve the word “death”. He may be a caffeine-converted robot, but there is no escaping what he was originally built for. However, I digress.\r\n\r\nIllegal Grounds, despite its name which implies a certain badness coupled with scary tattoos (or maybe the fact it was started by a lawyer?), is a very tame and inviting neighborhood coffee shop. Situated on the ground floor of an old Victorian house,  it embodies all the charms of a local favorite. Upon entrance, you walk straight down a hallway to the counter, and in my case, was met by a very friendly employee.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee.</span> An Americano was ordered and with it in hand, I turned the corner, entered the living room, and flopped down on one of the couches. Ultimately, I wasn''t going to expect much from the cup of coffee. The machine was automatic and they serve Illy coffee. Whenever I experience this kind of scenario, this usually translates to a very tame, albeit drinkable, cup of coffee. And I was right. There were no overwhelming flavors or distinctions to the espresso, just utilitarian goodness. I know I sound snooty when I immediately dismiss a beverage produced from an automatic machine, especially since this blog is called "Coffee Bot" which implies a certain level of automation, but understand that ultimately it is the human element in the creation of a beverage that gives it its ultimate dimension and uniqueness. It''s that human element that fuels my passion for exceptional coffee.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere.</span> The atmosphere didn''t disappoint. Once I rounded the corner into the seating area (or living room), I was immediately impressed with how many tables and chairs could fit amid the cozy space. A large picture window at the end of the room gave a bright, framed view of 17th street, and the light that poured in lit the walls full of local art. Wood floors, quiet music and a plentiful supply of power strips made Illegal Grounds a perfect spot to hunker down and get straight to conversation, work, or relaxation. <em>Take note: this place was pretty quiet despite the small crowd. To that end, if you are going to discuss the party habits of fellow world leaders and don''t want your secrets ending up on Wikileaks, this might not be the right place for those conversations. Alternatively, you could sit outside on the covered porch-there are far less people there. </em>\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The End.</span> Even though Bot1 didn''t fit easily between the tables and chairs, I would say our visit was a success and we will definitely return. The coffee gets the job done, the employees were very friendly,  and the atmosphere makes you want to hang around a little longer than you might at another coffee shop. <span class="end-icon">END</span>\r\n[mappress mapid="8"]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>', 'Illegal Grounds ', '<a href="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/illegal-grounds.jpg"><img src="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/illegal-grounds.jpg" alt="Illegal Grounds Coffee Shop" title="illegal-grounds" width="528" height="200" class="size-full wp-image-365" /></a>\r\nIllegal Grounds, despite its name which implies a certain badness coupled with scary tattoos (or maybe the fact it was started by a lawyer?), is a very tame and inviting neighborhood coffee shop. Situated on the ground floor of an old Victorian house,  it embodies all the charms of a local favorite. Upon entrance, you walk straight in down a hallway to the counter, and in my case, was met by a very friendly employee.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '364-revision-27', '', '', '2010-12-30 18:18:11', '2010-12-30 18:18:11', '', 364, 'http://coffeebot.co/coffee-shop-reviews/364-revision-27/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(518, 1, '2011-01-28 21:11:40', '2011-01-28 21:11:40', '<script src="http://connect.facebook.net/en_US/all.js#xfbml=1"></script><fb:like show_faces="true" width="450"></fb:like>\n<div id="rating-block">\n\n[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="4" cat1detail="Killer, well-crafted coffee" cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="3.5" cat2detail="Vibrant and unassuming"]\n<table id="info">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td class="title">Features <a title="key" href="http://coffeebot.co/about-2/symbol-key/">(Key)</a></td>\n\n<td><span class="no-atm">No ATM</span><span class="no-alcohol">No Alcohol</span><span class="no-music">Live Music</span><span class="yes-parking">Free Parking</span><span class="yes-food">Food is Served</span><span class="yes-wifi">Free Wifi</span><span class="manual">Manual Espresso Machine</span>\n</td>\n\n\n\n<td><span class="food">Food</span><span class="free-parking">free parking</span><span class="wifi">WiFi</span><span class="manual">manual</span><span class="atm">ATM</span></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class="address">2116 Pearl Street, Boulder, CO 80302 </td>\n<td class="phone">(303) 247-0124 </td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</div>\n\n<span class="first-words">“Espressoria” is in the name, why <em>wouldn''t</em> you go there?</span> I discovered this place while trying to go to another coffee shop that was completely packed. Bot1 has no patience for traffic or mobs of people, and when confronted with such situations, his programmed reaction is to drive 30 mph over the speed limit in one direction--stopping for no one. That''s even more dangerous considering the amount of college students and left-over hippies riding around on bicycles in this town. Had he not erupted in such acutely emulated anger, we would never have stumbled across Jet''s Espressoria—quaintly situated slightly off the beaten path in Boulder, Colorado.\n\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee.</span> An Americano was ordered, and it was presented to me in a mug and with a beautiful golden crema. As I sipped it, my mouth was filled with a wonderful rich, dense, and full-bodied flavor. It was exactly what I needed after riding in a Subaru with a crazed robot. The flavor held, and over the course of my stay the taste never turned extremely acidic, like some coffees tend to do as they cool. This was the work of a fine roast, great espresso skills, and a wonderful espresso machine. Based on a tweet from back in July, they serve Box Car Espresso, Novo Espresso, and Boulder Organic Espresso. For any of you who have read my other posts, you know you usually have me at “Novo”. Judging from the extremely steady stream of customers, they all agreed with the quality as well. \n\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere.</span> This place has a very local, neighborhood, some might say “indie” feel. I interpreted a loose 50''s vibe underscored by photographs of abandoned Route 66-style motels and gas stations, retro-looking tables and chairs and swirling ceiling fans. On the face of it, I personally am not a fan of this kind of look for a coffee shop, but I found myself quite comfortable and Bot1 felt he was among kin, being that most of his metal body work originated from the 50''s. It also had the dinge (which I''m beginning to think is a word I made up) factor I love so much: sketchy paint jobs, cluttered bar and counter, uneven tables and hand-written signs. It was also filled with the bicycle riding naturalists, designers, and college students that Bot1 nearly annihilated on the way over. In short, a great mix of people.\n\nJet''s Espressoria also bills itself as a bakery and their presentation of fine items was not lacking. Because of their $5 minimum for credit card use, I ordered a blueberry muffin as well. When I do these reviews I''m well aware that I am merely taking a snapshot of an overall experience and I allow quite a bit for less-than-great food, drink, or atmosphere, but this blueberry muffin was, well, not great. That said, I noticed most people going for their assortment of quiches and breakfast burritos which all looked wonderful, and next time I visit I will be digging in to one of these for sure. \n\n<span class="first-words">The End.</span> Overall this place was a killer find. The coffee quality is way up there and I am very willing to overlook the muffin disappointment in light of the fine coffee and atmosphere. The employees (owners?) were very friendly and seemed genuinely focused on providing an outstanding product. Bring cash or buy lots of stuff since they have a $5 charge minimum, and try it! <span class="end-icon">END</span>\n[mappress mapid="7"]\n<hr />\n<p style="text-align: center;">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\n<hr />', 'Jet''s Espressoria', 'I discovered this place while trying to go to another coffee shop that was completely packed. Bot1 has no patience for traffic or mobs of people, and when confronted with such situations, his programmed reaction is to drive 30 mph over the speed limit in one direction--stopping for no one. That''s even more dangerous considering the amount of college students and left-over hippies riding around on bicycles in this town. Had he not erupted in such acutely emulated anger, we would never have stumbled across Jet''s Espressoria—quaintly situated slightly off the beaten path in Boulder, Colorado.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '333-autosave', '', '', '2011-01-28 21:11:40', '2011-01-28 21:11:40', '', 333, 'http://coffeebot.co/coffee-shop-reviews/333-autosave/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
