(520, 1, '2010-12-30 18:20:00', '2010-12-30 18:20:00', '<script src="http://connect.facebook.net/en_US/all.js#xfbml=1"></script><fb:like show_faces="true" width="450"></fb:like>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\r\n<hr />\r\n<div id="rating-block">\r\n\r\n[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="2.5" cat1detail="Utilitarian coffee perfect for those all-night-ers." cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="3" cat2detail="Couches, bar and tables abound; lots of windows."]\r\n<table id="info">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="title">Features <a title="key" href="http://coffeebot.co/about-2/symbol-key/">(Key)</a></td>\r\n<td><span class="food">Food</span><span class="free-parking">free parking</span><span class="wifi">WiFi</span><span class="manual">manual</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="address">1795 Folsom St., Boulder, CO 80302</td>\r\n<td class="phone">(303) 440-8808</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="website"><a title="Folsom St Coffee" href="http://www.folsomstreetcoffee.com/">Website</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<span class="first-words">Bot1 had just completed a lecture at CU on the intricacies of wiring a common household goldfish,</span> and like he is after every lecture, found his system needing a certain caffeine boost. We found ourselves at Folsom St. Coffee Co. This is a college joint through and through, and the day we visited it was its usual self: packed, hip...and green. According to their website, Folsom St. Coffee is “Boulder''s only true eco-friendly coffeehouse. Folsom St. Coffee Co. was awarded the Eco-Cycle award for ''Zero Waste or Darn Near'' as well as the "Waste Reduction" award from the Center For Resource Conservation.” I believe it, because when Bot1 tried to throw away his trash, his waste eliminating algorithm caused his CPU to overheat just trying to sort out which tub to throw what in.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee.</span> As has become customary, a double espresso was ordered and Bot1 left to talk up a couple students who were sitting outside. The espresso presented to me had a deceivingly beautiful thick crema that held fast when I spooned some sugar on top. That was a good sign. The flavor, however, was a disappointment. Oddly enough I felt like I was drinking a lime. Of course there were most of the typical espresso qualities, but the acidity was shocking! I''d like to attribute this to the extraction of the shot, but I watched it pour and everything was on the up and up. The flavor evened out when it was in an Americano, but overall I wasn''t too impressed with the flavor.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere.</span>Like many coffee shops, however, the experience doesn''t always center around the coffee, and ultimately Folsom St. Coffee delivered in other areas. The atmosphere was welcoming, cozy and was the sort of place in which I felt I could get motivated to finally write my 20 page single-spaced essay on the relationship between Pyongyang and Beijing. The muddled and haphazard decor actually cemented the cozy feeling, and that constant murmur of a packed coffee house was ideal for working, meeting friends, or simply sipping a cup of coffee. Complete with poetry, open mic nights and live music acts, this place is hopping a good part of every day, and the sort of place young hipsters like to frequent.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The End.</span> Overall this coffee shop is very enjoyable, and despite being turned down three whole times, Bot1 vowed it wouldn''t keep him down and will definitely return. While the coffee didn''t bowl me over, if you keep it to lattes, Americanos, teas and brews you won''t be disappointed. <span class="end-icon">END</span>\r\n\r\n[mappress mapid="6"]', 'Folsom St. Coffee Company', 'Bot1 had just completed a lecture at CU on the intricacies of wiring a common household goldfish, and like he is after every lecture, found his system needing a certain caffeine boost. We found ourselves at Folsom St. Coffee Co. ', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '316-revision-22', '', '', '2010-12-30 18:20:00', '2010-12-30 18:20:00', '', 316, 'http://coffeebot.co/coffee-shop-reviews/316-revision-22/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(521, 1, '2010-12-30 18:20:31', '2010-12-30 18:20:31', '<p style="text-align: center;">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<a href="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/common-grounds.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-286" title="common-grounds" src="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/common-grounds.jpg" alt="common grounds coffee house" width="528" height="200" /></a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"></p>\r\n\r\n<div id="rating-block">\r\n\r\n[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="2.5" cat1detail="Care is taken in preparation, but overall espresso quality seems to be lacking." cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="3.5" cat2detail="Lot''s of seating, power outlets, local art, bright and natural light."]\r\n<table id="info">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="title">Features <a title="key" href="http://coffeebot.co/about-2/symbol-key/">(Key)</a></td>\r\n<td><span class="alcohol">alcohol</span><span class="food">Food</span><span class="paid-parking">paid and street parking</span><span class="wifi">WiFi</span><span class="manual">manual</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="address">1550 17th Street, Denver (LoDo Location)</td>\r\n<td class="phone">(303) 296-9248</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="website"><a title="Common Grounds Coffee House" href="http://www.commongroundscoffeehouse.com/">Website</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<span class="first-words">It was a quiet day. A little bored, Bot1 insisted we consult my very-cute-coffee-name-pun list</span> to see if something piqued our interest, and it was then we decided on Common Grounds Coffee House. <a href="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/deathbeam.jpg"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-308" title="deathbeam" src="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/deathbeam.jpg" alt="deathbeam" width="250" height="188" /></a>While usually passionate about the coffee (passion being one of Bot1''s few emulated emotions), Bot1 was more interested in reading “Death Beam”, a title he''d spotted on the bookshelf, and while I always try to discourage him reading anything with “death” in it, I decided to pick my battle and allow it. Bot1 then marched up to the counter, emitted his demand for a whole milk latte and a double espresso, beamed the book off the shelf, and proceeded to process the pages via his OCR scanner.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee.</span> As usual, I was left with the coffee. The person who made the drinks was extremely friendly (bonus) and after a pleasant interaction about the weather she proceeded to focus in on the latte. I noticed she took much care when steaming the milk and while I couldn''t see the shots as they were extracted, the aroma was enticing and the shots were swiftly combined with the milk. I was given the latte which embodied thick, dense foam, slight hints of brown espresso swirled through the mix, and a warmth that was comforting on that chilly day. Ultimately, however, the flavor, while it didn''t disappoint, was only average. To be certain, it was a good latte—one I would return for—but  once again the reality was that to have truly impressive beverages, the coffee itself must be spectacular, and it just wasn''t. The double espresso disappointed slightly as well. The crema was thin and nearly immediately broke to reveal the dark body of the shot. The“raining” effect or separation of the shot was reminiscent of Guinness, which, as luck would have it, is served at Common Grounds as well. The flavor didn''t go deep enough either. The initial stark bitterness never really left my tongue and the acidity was slightly overwhelming, so much so that any dimension that might have been there was masked by this intensity.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere.</span> Common Grounds embodied a balanced mix of the old and new. The counter and bar were your typical curvy-bistro-coolness with lots of angles thrown in that made for exciting visuals. There was plenty of room to sprawl out on one of their two very large tables, or keep to yourself on any one of their abundant four-seaters. One feature Bot1 and I liked a lot was the presence of bookshelves with actual physical books. On top of that, if one so desired, one could pick up and read...one. During my visit I did notice a young guy in skinny pants with his Mac under his arm stroking his chin in silent wonder at the spectacle of these books, but for the most part people knew what to do with them. Large windows overlooking the busy street allowed generous amounts of light in, illuminating the local art canvases aiding in a vibrant feel; and the constant murmur of machines, music, and conversation were all at the perfect level.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The End.</span> Common Grounds Coffee House withstands the test. Sure, I wasn''t bowled over by the coffee, but in the end it was <em>good</em>. Combined with the atmosphere and friendliness of the employees, it''s definitely a place you should check out. Bot1 agrees and also informed me “Death Beam” didn''t live up to his planet domination aspirations...much to my relief.<span class="end-icon">END</span>\r\n\r\n[mappress mapid="4"]<!--more-->', 'Common Grounds Coffee House', '<a href="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/common-grounds.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-286" title="common-grounds" src="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/common-grounds.jpg" alt="common grounds coffee house" width="528" height="200" /></a>\r\nIt was a quiet day. A little bored, Bot1 insisted we consult my very-cute-coffee-name-pun list to see if something piqued our interest, and it was then we decided on Common Grounds Coffee House. While usually passionate about the coffee (passion being one of Bot1''s few emulated emotions), Bot1 was more interested in reading “Death Beam”, a title he''d spotted on the bookshelf, and while I always try to discourage him reading anything with “death” in it', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '301-revision-16', '', '', '2010-12-30 18:20:31', '2010-12-30 18:20:31', '', 301, 'http://coffeebot.co/coffee-shop-reviews/301-revision-16/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(522, 1, '2010-12-22 14:09:53', '2010-12-22 14:09:53', '<p style="text-align: center;">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: left;"></p>\r\n\r\n<hr /><a href="http://www.coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/paris-platte.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-138" title="Paris On The Platte" src="http://www.coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/paris-platte.jpg" alt="Paris On The Platte" width="530" height="200" /></a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<div id="rating-block">\r\n\r\n[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="3" cat1detail="Utilitarian caffeine with modest attention to quality." cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="3.5" cat2detail="Dark where it needs to be, light where it''s important, local art and aged/warehouse character"]\r\n<table id="info">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="title">Features <a title="key" href="http://www.coffeebot.co/?page_id=195">(Key)</a></td>\r\n<td><span class="alcohol">Alcohol</span><span class="food">Food</span><span class="paid-parking">Free parking</span><span class="wifi">WiFi</span><span class="manual">Manual Machine</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="address">1553 Platte St, Denver, CO 80202</td>\r\n<td class="phone">(303) 455-2451</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="website"><a title="Paris On The Platte" href="http://www.parisontheplattecafeandbar.com">Website</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<span class="first-words">Paris on the Platte is one of my favorite urban coffee bars in the Denver metro.</span> It has all the great ''cool factors'': local art that is usually good, a store-front facing a lively street, weathered decor,  indie rock (I walked in to Viva Voce playing over the speakers—one of my favorite bands), citizens in skinny jeans, and decent espresso. It''s a great place being not only a coffee shop, but also a cafe and bar.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee</span> Bot1 showed up in a pair of skinny jeans he had purchased from the Salvation Army, and after I wrestled them off of him, he sulked up to the counter and ordered a small latte. Even though we ordered a small, it came in a nice big mug, and after some detailed chemical analysis, Bot1 concluded the cinnamon on top of the foam was in fact, cinnamon. A nice touch, but if you don''t like people putting spices on your coffee, you might mention that upon ordering. After this, he lost interest, went over to the bar, and I was left to do the tasting by myself.\r\n\r\nThe latte was...good; nothing amazing. The foam was a tad bubbly and I would have liked more espresso presence, but the flavor that was there was smooth and balanced, so I can''t really complain. This isn''t an artisan place, so I didn''t detect much passion for coffee itself; I understand that coffee passion isn''t necessarily the point to the place.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere</span> The main thing about this joint is that you can come in, set up your lappy, and do what you do best: hit up Facebook. Keep in mind that most people who sit there for a while are also on their laptops, so the connection speed is pretty slow. So, if you''re heading there to play Warcraft, it might not be the best place. Then again, you probably wouldn''t actually head outside to go to a coffee shop, either.\r\n\r\nAnother great aspect is the presence of living, breathing people (not just spoiled robots), and at this place, the flow of humans is pretty constant. Of all the times I have visited, I''ve never seen it empty, and I like that. The steady murmur of conversation is the perfect soundtrack to get my work done. It definitely is a neighborhood staple, and you aren''t without choices on where to sit or plug in. There''s plenty of room in the coffee side, bar side, and there''s even a little patio outback where cigarettes tend to be smoked.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The End</span> Overall, it''s a good place, and I find myself recommending it often. Bot1 even likes it, but I can''t be sure the presence of wine next door is not swaying his judgment.<span class="end-icon">END</span>\r\n\r\n[mappress mapid="1"]', 'Paris on the Platte Cafe &amp; Bar', 'Paris on the Platte is one of my favorite urban coffee bars in the Denver metro. It has all the great ''cool factors'': local art that is usually good, a store-front facing a busy, lively street, beaten-up decor,  indie rock (I walked in to Viva Voce playing-one of my fav''s), citizens in skinny jeans, and decent espresso. It''s a unique place being not only a coffee shop, but also a wine bar.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '121-revision-10', '', '', '2010-12-22 14:09:53', '2010-12-22 14:09:53', '', 121, 'http://coffeebot.co/coffee-shop-reviews/121-revision-10/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
