(523, 1, '2010-12-22 14:10:22', '2010-12-22 14:10:22', '<p style="text-align: center;">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<div id="rating-block">\r\n\r\n[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="4.5" cat1detail="The focus is on the coffee here. Conversation, craftmanship and quality prove that point." cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="2" cat2detail="Tables were very uncomfortable and the overall decor left something to be desired. "]\r\n<table id="info">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="title">Features <a title="key" href="http://www.coffeebot.co/?page_id=195">(Key)</a></td>\r\n<td><span class="free-parking">Free parking</span><span class="wifi">WiFi</span><span class="manual">Manual Machine</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="address">7745 Wadsworth Boulevard, Arvada, CO 80003</td>\r\n<td class="phone">(303) 424-1313</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="website"><a title="Two Rivers Coffee" href="http://www.tworiverscoffee.com/">Website</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<span class="first-words">On a very hot day back in July</span> I came across Two Rivers Coffee. I stumbled in to the quiet, unassuming shop which promptly had me sold when I saw them using the Clover brewing system. Not only that, they served Novo Coffee, a gem in Colorado''s roasting crown. That said, it was hot, and I needed something cool.<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee</span> The person working there, who I later found out was the owner, convinced me to try what he called a "toddy", or a cold brewed coffee. I say convinced, because I am a pretty staunch hot coffee kind of guy. Bot1 couldn''t compute the concept of cold coffee, and already being overheated from the 90 degree outside temps, inadvertently went into hibernate mode before his processor overheated. However, I accepted. The cold brew turned out to be exactly what I needed on that hot day. Unlike other iced coffees that I''ve had which usually capitalize on overwhelmingly acidic, citrus notes to fool you in to thinking you''re being refreshed, there was a general lack of acidity which was replaced with a surprisingly deep, smooth palette of caramel and earth tones. Not at all what I expected from a cold coffee. A hint of spice lingered on my tongue and the aftertaste, despite the overall intensity, was very pleasant. The flavor lasted, as well, and despite being slightly watered down from the ice, my last sip was just as good as the first. I was sold.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere</span>As for the other important aspects to the shop: service and atmosphere, there are a few more notes to ad. Since I was served by the owner, I was immediately engaged in pleasant conversation and was able to talk for a fair amount of time about coffee, asking questions, etc., and he was more than willing to chat. I get the vibe that it''s an atmosphere he tries to foster. And, speaking of atmosphere, well, you don''t go there for it. The tables were uncomfortable, especially for the lengthy amount of time I was there (waiting on Bot1 to wake up), the blue walls made me nervous, and the local art display, while well-intentioned, was haphazard and not well organized.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The End</span><span style="color: #999999;"><em>(A note here: this original review was written back in July and I have since seen they are doing some work on the place, so the atmosphere complaint might be a moot point)</em></span> None of that would keep me from there, however, because this is the kind of coffee shop you go to for the superb coffee, you don''t have to go there for anything else. I strongly recommend you go and enjoy some of the highest quality coffee available here at 5,280 feet. <span class="end-icon">END</span>\r\n\r\n[mappress mapid="2"]', 'Two Rivers Coffee', 'On a very hot day back in July I came across Two Rivers Coffee. I stumbled in to the quiet, unassuming shop which promptly had me sold when I saw them using the Clover brewing system.That said, it was hot, and I needed something cool.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '52-revision-12', '', '', '2010-12-22 14:10:22', '2010-12-22 14:10:22', '', 52, 'http://coffeebot.co/coffee-shop-reviews/52-revision-12/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(524, 1, '2010-12-22 14:10:38', '2010-12-22 14:10:38', '<a href="http://www.coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/09/forza.jpg"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-280" title="forza" src="http://www.coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2010/09/forza.jpg" alt="Forza Coffee" width="528" height="200" /></a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<div id="rating-block">\r\n\r\n[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="3.5" cat1detail="The employees seem to care &amp; their product, and the result is a decent product." cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="3.5" cat2detail="Lot''s of seating, fireplace, power outlets, local art, competent interior design."]\r\n<table id="info">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="title">Features <a title="key" href="http://www.coffeebot.co/?page_id=195">(Key)</a></td>\r\n<td><span class="food">Food</span><span class="free-parking">Free parking</span><span class="wifi">WiFi</span><span class="manual">WiFi</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="address">3013 W. 104th Ave. Ste. 700, Westminster, CO 80031</td>\r\n<td class="phone">(303) 465-0605</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="website"><a title="Forza Coffee" href="http://www.rmforzacoffee.com">Website</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<span class="first-words">I was trying to decide which coffee house to review first for CoffeeBot.</span> Not the most easy decision to make considering here in the Denver metro area we have close to 10 x 8 to the third carry the two coffee shops. OK, not that many, but still. Luckily, Bot1 made the decision for me, and it''s a good one: Forza Coffee in Westminster. I know, I know, a suburban coffee shop, but bear with me...<!--more-->\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The History</span> From what I know about this place, its pedigree is traced back to Tacoma, Washington—not a bad place to come from, I suppose. Their self-description talks of being a vital part of the community and being inspired by Italy''s espresso culture, yada yada yada. Nearly everyone says that. Even Howard Schultz said that at one time and look where that got us. However, their expressed desire to be a neighborhood coffee shop seems to actually be working.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee</span> My standard first-time drink is usually an Americano or latte. In this case, the Americano is a wonderful baseline drink. If made correctly, you get a lovely crema, the hot water and espresso combination even out the flavor of the coffee, and let''s face it: espresso is gone way too fast. I''m not Italian, for Pete''s sake. I love espresso shots but will only drink it straight in places I really trust. To my delight, I heard the familiar banging of portafilters into bins, and I had a feeling I was in for a treat. The drink was produced and brought to my table, whereupon I viewed that  nice layer of crema. The flavor was good. Not amazing, but good. The espresso certainly embodied everything a fine espresso should: full body, slight bitterness, subtle caramel tones; but for me, the dimension didn''t go far enough. That''s hardly a negative, since the intensity of espresso is, after all, subjective.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere</span> For once, this is a suburban coffee shop that is actually comfortable and has a hint of urban dinge that in my opinion, all the best coffee shops have. Sometimes, the dingier the better. The deep yellow-gold, black, copper and dark wood mix well to form a comfortable and inspiring atmosphere. Armed with a great comfy-couch area and plenty of tables (including outside seating) you definitely have your choice of places to sit. Mine, however, was by the fireplace. And that''s enough about the design, I drink coffee, after all.\r\n<span class="first-words">The End</span> Finally, the experience was punctuated by genuinely nice staff. I''ve been a few times, and even Bot1 has sneaked over there a couple times when I haven''t been looking. Witty small talk and a staff that calls  you by name on the second visit is a good step in the direction of having a lasting neighborhood coffee shop.<span class="end-icon">END</span>\r\n[mappress mapid="3"]\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>', 'Forza Coffee', 'I was trying to decide which coffee house to review first for Coffee-Bot. Not the most easy decision to make considering here in the Denver metro area we have close to 10 x 8 to the third carry the two...coffee shops. OK, not that many, but still. Luckily, Bot1 made the decision for me, and it''s a good one: Forza Coffee in Westminster. I know, I know, a suburban coffee shop, but bear with me...', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '160-revision-13', '', '', '2010-12-22 14:10:38', '2010-12-22 14:10:38', '', 160, 'http://coffeebot.co/coffee-shop-reviews/160-revision-13/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
