(542, 2, '2011-02-07 15:18:45', '2011-02-07 15:18:45', '<script src="http://connect.facebook.net/en_US/all.js#xfbml=1"></script><fb:like show_faces="true" width="450"></fb:like>\r\n\r\n<div id="rating-block">\r\n[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="4" cat1detail="Serious & Sexy" cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="4" cat2detail="Artistically hip and comfortably welcoming"]\r\n<table id="info">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="title">Features <a title="key" href="http://coffeebot.co/about-2/symbol-key/">(Key)</a></td>\r\n<td><span class="no-atm">No ATM</span><span class="no-alcohol">No Alcohol</span><span class="live-music">Live Music</span><span class="pay-parking">Paid Parking</span><span class="yes-food">Food is Served</span><span class="yes-wifi">Free Wifi</span><span class="manual">Manual Espresso Machine</span>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="address">Mon - Sat</td>\r\n<td class="address">6:30am - 11:00pm</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="address">Sun</td>\r\n<td class="address">7:00am - 11:00pm</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="address">940 Pearl St., Boulder, CO 80304</td>\r\n<td class="phone">303.443.3133</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="website"><a href="http://tridentcafe.com">Website</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<span class="first-words">Confession: I, Bot6, have an irrational (possibly unhealthy) obsession with those archaic bits of paper sewn together</span> and marketed to hopeless nostalgics as “books.” Bot1 recommends a program upgrade to digital browsing, but I am nothing if not stubborn. I dragged Bot1 into Trident’s bookstore, leading him through the cozy nooks and tall shelves crammed with leather-bound covers and musty paperbacks, but he still doesn’t “get me.” Fortunately, Trident hosts an adjoining café that nearly always draws customers in with a delightful aroma of coffee, chai spice, and peppermint (those who are familiar with the general Eau de Boulder—a tantalizing mix of hung-over co-eds, stale doobies, and unwashed hippies—will appreciate this triumph). \r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee.</span> Bot1 mumbled something about “intervention,” as he dragged me away from the brink of purchasing a fourth copy of Paradise Lost to the café counter. Though I’ve spent many an afternoon enjoying Trident’s artsy/cozy atmosphere, this was the first time I ordered coffee. Until today, I’d been systematically working my way through their wall of loose-leaf tea options (which they serve with a mug and a tiny personal tea pot), but I sensed Bot1 evaluating our friendship after my book-ogling, so I decided to follow his lead and order an Americano ($2.20). The barista was friendly, without forcing an artificial chattiness, and served my beautiful drink in a beer glass (the other option was a darling thimble-cup that would have left even Barbie with a severe case of caffeine deprivation). The glass showcased a beautiful crema; I hadn’t seen an Americano this sexy since I made them myself. I added a few drops of milk, but I needn’t even have done that. Trident’s espresso is smooth and well-balanced, while still maintaining a hearty richness, though some might prefer a “boulder” taste (hahaha—get it? “Boulder?” No? Oh, fine). \r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere.</span> We carried our drinks past rows of local photography displays (and a toasty woodstove) to the back of the café, where we fortunately found an empty booth. Though usually busy, Trident doesn’t seem to draw the typical student/tourist set. Instead, its location at the west end of Pearl St., and the fact that it has been around for over 20 years, attracts the local community—professors, grad students, environmentalists, business-owners, etc. The back patio sports a sand-box, so beware children. And pigeons. Inside, the storefront windows, exposed brick walls, and high ceiling create a comfortably bright atmosphere, although it can be slightly dark at night. Also, I fear our booth’s last occupant was a tamed wildebeest, judging from the gaping bum-crater in the seat cushion. Even perching on the crater’s ample rim, I needed a phone book to reach the table properly, which was bolted to the wall so that I also had to reach forward to scribble my notes. I recommend a regular table. \r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The End.</span> Overall, Trident has perfected the balance between artistically hip and comfortably welcoming—like your impossibly cool, non-elitist friend who loves you despite your nerdy tendencies and bad puns. <span class="end-icon-bot6">END</span>\r\n[mappress mapid="12"]\r\n<hr />\r\n<p style="text-align: center">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\r\n<h2>What do you think?</h2>\r\n', 'Trident Booksellers and Cafe ', '...Trident hosts an adjoining café that nearly always draws customers in with a delightful aroma of coffee, chai spice, and peppermint (those who are familiar with the general Eau de Boulder—a tantalizing mix of hung-over co-eds, stale doobies, and unwashed hippies—will appreciate this triumph). ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'trident-booksellers-and-cafe', '', '', '2011-03-05 14:14:41', '2011-03-05 14:14:41', '', 0, 'http://coffeebot.co/?p=542', 0, 'post', '', 1),
