ne, eh?”. This is a place I had to visit. “Redefine(ing)” can be dangerous. Bot1 once tried to redefine rock. That''s how the world got prog-rock. Hopefully the coffee shop ''redefinement'' turns out a bit better. Bot1 was also excited to visit since there were computers he could use instead of relying on his 28k on-board modem to download 25 minute drum solos. So, we headed for the shop and arrived barely out of the shadows of downtown''s skyscrapers in an uncomfortably sterile neighborhood of condos and street shops.\r\n\r\nMy first impression of the place was positive and not at all what I expected after checking the shop''s website (which doesn''t do the place any justice). It was packed with city peeps when we arrived and I wound my way through tables and urbanites to the counter where I was welcomed by a large overhead menu and a not so welcoming, too-cool-for-school barista. \r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee. </span>I ordered a double espresso ($1.80) and Bot1 went for the mocha (medium:$3.50). The espresso was presented in a demitasse and I couldn''t wait to have my first sip. Once again, I stumbled on a place serving Novo coffee and was eager to see how it emerged from the machine. The first sip flashed with a bright acidity that yielded a complex cluster of flavors reminding me a bit of peanut butter—I was happy. It wasn''t the best espresso I''ve had but as the foundation to the rest of the beverages it was quality nonetheless. The mocha was fairly good as well (I sneaked a sip while Bot1 configured his IP address) although it was a bit sweet. It''s also worth noting that this truly is a good place for the coffee aficionado since I saw numerous french presses and am pretty sure some pourover coffee magic. \r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere. </span>What really makes Fluid Coffee tick is what I mentioned in the beginning of this post: coffee shop ''redefinement-ation-ing''. There is an abundance of places to sit, relax, work, and plug in. This is no internet cafe of the old days when shifty old guys hovered over bulky computers that were crammed against the walls of dingy, fluorescent-lit rooms sipping over-extracted, stale coffee. Instead you have flat panels, windows (so you''re not completely cut off from the world), shifty lawyers instead of shifty old guys, and superb coffee. Okay, I concede a bit of redefining. Fluid coffee has filled every nook with something for the customer: books, magazines, art, computers, and a [new] room full of tables that you can reserve for yourself or your team. You also don''t have to be without those office amenities if you are working remotely. For a fee, you are able to print and copy your top secret documents or the next great American novel. There is even a large column right next to the counter plastered with adverts and business cards so you can get ye-self out there and get discovered. Finally, I found the atmosphere fairly inspirational: multicolored walls, comfortable seating, clutter, conversational murmur, and a diversity of patrons did well to get the juices flowing. It''s the sort of place Bot1 and I can fit in with no brow-raising—it''s truly a neighborhood coffee shop. \r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The End. </span>So, does it redefine the coffee shop experience? They certainly make it easy for the incognito professional to have place to work, serve outstanding coffee, and manage to do all this without being a creepy internet cafe. Fluid coffee has found a great mix of community, casual, and professional. At the same time, it''s still only a coffee shop: one that neither wowed or excited me, but one that I most definitely will recommend to others and visit again...and again. <span class="end-icon-bot2">END</span>\r\n[mappress mapid="13"]\r\n<p style="text-align: center;">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\r\n', 'Fluid Coffee Bar', '<a href="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/fluid.jpg"><img src="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/fluid.jpg" alt="fluid coffee bar" title="fluid coffee bar" width="525" height="199" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-592" /></a>\r\n\r\nA friend mentioned a place in uptown Denver that was attempting to re-define the coffee shop experience.</span> “Redefine, eh?”. This is a place I had to visit. “Redefine(ing)” can be dangerous. Bot1 once tried to redefine rock. That''s how the world got prog-rock. Hopefully the coffee shop ''redefinement'' turns out a bit better. Bot1 was also excited to visit since there were computers he could use instead of relying on his 28k on-board modem to download 25 minute drum solos. So, we headed for the shop and arrived barely out of the shadows of downtown''s skyscrapers in an uncomfortably sterile neighborhood of condos and street shops.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'fluid-coffee-bar', '', '', '2011-03-05 14:14:09', '2011-03-05 14:14:09', '', 0, 'http://coffeebot.co/?p=589', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(545, 1, '2011-02-05 20:40:26', '2011-02-05 20:40:26', 'Confession: I, Bot6, have an irrational (possibly unhealthy) obsession with those archaic bits of paper sewn together and marketed to hopeless nostalgics as “books.” Bot1 recommends a program upgrade to digital browsing, but I am nothing if not stubborn. I dragged Bot1 into Trident’s bookstore, leading him through the cozy nooks and tall shelves crammed with leather-bound covers and musty paperbacks, but he still doesn’t “get me.” Fortunately, Trident hosts an adjoining café that nearly always draws customers in with a delightful aroma of coffee, chai spice, and peppermint (those who are familiar with the general Eau de Boulder—a tantalizing mix of hung-over co-eds, stale doobies, and unwashed hippies—will appreciate this triumph). \r\n\r\nBot1 mumbled something about “intervention,” as he dragged me away from the brink of purchasing a fourth copy of Paradise Lost to the café counter. Though I’ve spent many an afternoon enjoying Trident’s artsy/cozy atmosphere, this was the first time I ordered coffee. Until today, I’d been systematically working my way through their wall of loose-leaf tea options (which they serve with a mug and a tiny personal tea pot), but I sensed Bot1 evaluating our friendship after my book-ogling, so I decided to follow his lead and order an Americano ($2.20). The barista was friendly, without forcing an artificial chattiness, and served my beautiful drink in a beer glass (the other option was a darling thimble-cup that would have left even Barbie with a severe case of caffeine deprivation). The glass showcased a beautiful crema; I hadn’t seen an Americano this sexy since I made them myself. I added a few drops of milk, but I needn’t even have done that. Trident’s espresso is smooth and well-balanced, while still maintaining a hearty richness, though some might prefer a “boulder” taste (hahaha—get it? “Boulder?” No? Oh, fine). \r\n\r\nWe carried our drinks past rows of local photography displays (and a toasty woodstove) to the back of the café, where we fortunately found an empty booth. Though usually busy, Trident doesn’t seem to draw the typical student/tourist set. Instead, it’s location at the west end of Pearl St., and the fact that it has been around for over 20 years, attracts the local community—professors, grad students, environmentalists, business-owners, etc. The back patio sports a sand-box, so beware children. And pigeons. Inside, the storefront windows, exposed brick walls, and high ceiling create a comfortably bright atmosphere, although it can be slightly dark at night. Also, I fear our booth’s last occupant was a tamed wildebeest, judging from the gaping bum-crater in the seat cushion. Even perching on the crater’s ample rim, I needed a phone book to reach the table properly, which was bolted to the wall so that I also had to reach forward to scribble my notes. I recommend a regular table. \r\n\r\nOverall, Trident has perfected the balance between artistically hip and comfortably welcoming—like your impossibly cool, non-elitist friend who loves you despite your nerdy tendencies and bad puns.\r\n', 'Trident Booksellers and Café ', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '542-revision-2', '', '', '2011-02-05 20:40:26', '2011-02-05 20:40:26', '', 542, 'http://coffeebot.co/coffee-shop-reviews/542-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
