 fourth copy of Paradise Lost to the café counter. Though I’ve spent many an afternoon enjoying Trident’s artsy/cozy atmosphere, this was the first time I ordered coffee. Until today, I’d been systematically working my way through their wall of loose-leaf tea options (which they serve with a mug and a tiny personal tea pot), but I sensed Bot1 evaluating our friendship after my book-ogling, so I decided to follow his lead and order an Americano ($2.20). The barista was friendly, without forcing an artificial chattiness, and served my beautiful drink in a beer glass (the other option was a darling thimble-cup that would have left even Barbie with a severe case of caffeine deprivation). The glass showcased a beautiful crema; I hadn’t seen an Americano this sexy since I made them myself. I added a few drops of milk, but I needn’t even have done that. Trident’s espresso is smooth and well-balanced, while still maintaining a hearty richness, though some might prefer a “boulder” taste (hahaha—get it? “Boulder?” No? Oh, fine). \n\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere.</span> We carried our drinks past rows of local photography displays (and a toasty woodstove) to the back of the café, where we fortunately found an empty booth. Though usually busy, Trident doesn’t seem to draw the typical student/tourist set. Instead, it’s location at the west end of Pearl St., and the fact that it has been around for over 20 years, attracts the local community—professors, grad students, environmentalists, business-owners, etc. The back patio sports a sand-box, so beware children. And pigeons. Inside, the storefront windows, exposed brick walls, and high ceiling create a comfortably bright atmosphere, although it can be slightly dark at night. Also, I fear our booth’s last occupant was a tamed wildebeest, judging from the gaping bum-crater in the seat cushion. Even perching on the crater’s ample rim, I needed a phone book to reach the table properly, which was bolted to the wall so that 