(563, 1, '2011-02-11 20:27:21', '2011-02-11 20:27:21', '<p style="text-align: center;">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\r\n<span class="first-words">I know, </span>we can all find our favorite coffee shop to get that essential coffee fix, and for a lot of people, it''s also tons better than what they prepare at home. This is especially the case for the majority of brewed coffee drinkers out there. Preparing excellent coffee at home is not really that hard; it''s also not really that time consuming. With the right tools and the right ingredients you can rival anything you find in a coffee shop. Look, If you are completely okay with coffee that comes from a plastic tub or out of the machine at 7-11, this post probably won''t mean much to you. If, however, you want that quality cup but don''t want to spend the $2 every day, or you want to impress your guests with killer coffee and dessert, this just might help you out. The rest of this post assumes you are striving for excellence every time you make coffee in your casa.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Tools...</span>\r\nFor every project, you have to have the right tools to get the job done well. For this post, we''ll be making coffee via French press, so, here''s what you''ll need:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>French press</li>\r\n	<li>grinder: blade or burr</li>\r\n	<li>kettle</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<span class="first-words">The Ingredients...</span>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>whole bean coffee</li>\r\n	<li>filtered water</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">Water is Key!</span>\r\nFirst off, your coffee is only as good as your water! The number one important element of good coffee is water! Think about it: coffee is 98% H2O, so if your water tastes bad, chances are your coffee will as well even if you are using $50/lb coffee. You don''t have to have an expensive reverse osmosis system to achieve good water; a simple water filtering pitcher, or even bottled drinking water will do the trick.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee.</span>\r\nOkay, for (good) coffee beans, I recommend you pop down to your local coffee shop and purchase a half or full pound of beans. Don''t know what to get? Just ask, they are usually more than willing to chat and help you pick a roast. Shops often sell what they serve, so if there is a particular brew you really enjoy, grab a pound of that. It is also possible to find good beans in the grocery store, but it''s a little harder and you don''t really know if it''s good or not until you try it. Here''s a tip: in my experience, anything labeled with the generic descriptor “gourmet”  is a complete flop and I would avoid it like the plague. The same goes when I visit a restaurants and cafes. Most self-respecting roasters and coffee shops no longer use this term.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">Grind Your Coffee As You Go </span>\r\nThis may seem like quite a burden each time you make coffee, but here''s why you want to grind as you go: once coffee has been roasted, oxygen becomes its mortal enemy and immediately the flavors in the oils begin to evaporate and the bean begins to sour. This is why coffee beans arrive in air-tight packages protected from all that nasty oxygen. Furthermore, when you grind coffee, you compromise the flavor''s ''housing'' and add more surface area for the beans to spoil, giving the ground coffee a very, very short shelf life. For the richest flavor, only purchase as much coffee as you will drink in a week, keep it sealed in its original package or a canister, and grind as you go. Side note: don''t keep your beans in the fridge or freezer. Doing this doesn''t prolong its life; in fact,  the coffee absorbs all those lovely refrigerator aromas (expired-potato-salad-pong-flavored Kona, anyone?). Keep the beans in a sealed container at room temperature and your coffee will stay its most flavorful and least corrupted.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">Proportion.</span>\r\nThis depends on you and your taste buds, actually, but a general rule is one tablespoon per cup. A lot of places talk about proportions in grams, but not too many of us have an accurate kitchen scale laying around, so forget that. A typical French press holds 8 cups of liquid, therefore use 8 tbs. If I''m in an economical mood I sometimes do 7 tbs to 8 cups, but any less than that would leave your coffee tasting pretty watered down. You can increase it a bit if you really want an intense flavor, but I wouldn''t go more than 1 or 2 tablespoons over that or the flavor will be uncomfortably intense.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">Temperature (Water again). </span>\r\nGet that water hot! An electric kettle works great if you have one, but use some method of boiling your water, even if it''s in a saucepan. The target temp is around 200 degrees Fahrenheit, so right after the water hits a boil let it settle down, and then pour it into the press making sure to saturate all the grounds. Caution: don''t burn the coffee! The flavor is extracted from the beans best around the 200 degree mark. If the water is any hotter, the coffee will taste over-extracted (bitter) and burnt.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">Time it!</span>\r\nIt''s really important for the coffee and water to mix promiscuously allowing the oils to saturate and brew. 4 minutes allows this to be accomplished. If you are really striving for that cup of perfection, pour the water evenly over the grounds and fill the press a quarter full. Let the grounds then sit for a minute and “bloom”--then at the end of the minute, add the rest of the water and stir. If you don''t want to do that, just pour the water in all at once and give it a good stir.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">Plunge it! </span>\r\nWhen four minutes are up, drive all the grounds to the bottom with the plunger. In most cases the plunger screens the grounds so that they don''t get into your cup. If you do get a couple, have no fear, they are not out to get you.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">Drink it! </span>\r\nEnjoy this beautiful beverage! \r\n\r\nSo does this seem like a lot of work? Let''s think about it: depending on the elevation where you live, it takes somewhere around 2 to 4 minutes for water to boil. During that time I grab all my stuff: the press (I make sure it''s clean), grind the coffee, add it to the press, grab my cups, etc. and by the time everything is together the water is ready. I pour, and I set my timer to 4 minutes. You can do the math; it''s about six to eight minutes from start to finish. That''s just about the same time as a conventional brewer.\r\n\r\nBelow is a video you can watch to see how easy it really is. Enjoy :)\r\n\r\n<iframe src="http://player.vimeo.com/video/19587209?byline=0&amp;portrait=0&amp;color=ff9933" width="525" height="295" frameborder="0"></iframe><p><a href="http://vimeo.com/19587209">French Press Style</a> from <a href="http://vimeo.com/user5878817">Christan Fergus</a> on <a href="http://vimeo.com">Vimeo</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n', 'Make Good Coffee at Home: French Press Style', 'I know, we can all find our favorite coffee shop to get that essential coffee fix, and for a lot of people, it''s also tons better than what they prepare at home. This is especially the case for the majority of brewed coffee drinkers out there. Preparing excellent coffee at home is not really that hard; it''s also not really that time consuming. With the right tools and the right ingredients you can rival anything you find in a coffee shop. \r\n<iframe src="http://player.vimeo.com/video/19587209?byline=0&amp;portrait=0&amp;color=ff9933" width="525" height="295" frameborder="0"></iframe>', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'make-good-coffee-at-home-french-press-style', '', '', '2011-02-14 14:17:07', '2011-02-14 14:17:07', '', 0, 'http://coffeebot.co/?p=563', 0, 'post', '', 1);
