(565, 1, '2011-02-09 16:07:22', '2011-02-09 16:07:22', '<p>[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\r\nI know, we can all find our favorite coffee shop to get that essential coffee fix, and for a lot of people, it''s also tons better than what they prepare at home. This is especially the case for the majority of brewed coffee drinkers out there. But I''m here to tell you, you too can have amazing coffee at home! It''s not really that hard, it''s also not really that time consuming, you just need the right tools and the right ingredients. If you are completely okay with coffee that comes in a plastic tub or what you can grab out of the machine at 7-11, this post probably won''t mean much to you. But, if you are one of those who want that quality cup but don''t want to spend the $2 every day, or the host who wants to impress their guests with killer coffee and desert,  this just might help you out. The rest of this post assumes you are striving for excellence every time you make coffee in your casa and I will treat you accordingly. \r\n\r\n1.The Tools\r\nLike every project, you have to have the right tools to get the job done well. For this post, we''ll be making coffee via French press. So, you''ll need a-you guessed it-french press, a way to boil water, a timer and of course, coffee.\r\n2.Water is Key!\r\nFirst off, Your coffee is only as good as your water! The number one trick to good coffee is not the coffee but the water! Think about it: coffee is 98% H2O, so if your water tastes bad, chances are your coffee will as well even if you are using $50/lb coffee. You don''t have to have an expensive reverse osmosis system to achieve good water; a simple water filtering pitcher or even bottled drinking water will do the trick.\r\n3.The Coffee\r\nOkay, so for the good coffee beans, I recommend you pop down to your local coffee shop and purchase a half or full pound of beans. Don''t know what to get? Just ask, they are usually more than willing to chat and help you pick a roast. Shops often sell what they serve, so if there is a particular brew you really enjoy, grab a pound of that. It is also possible to find good beans in the grocery store but it''s a little harder and you don''t really know if it''s good or not until you try it. Here''s a tip: in my experience, anything with “gourmet” on the label is a complete flop and I would stay away from it like the plague. The same goes when I visit a restaurant or cafe and they describe their coffee as “gourmet”. This is a generic descriptor and most self-respecting roasters and coffee shops no longer use this term. \r\n4.Grind your coffee as you go\r\nIf you are not used to doing this, it may seem like quite a burden each time you make coffee, but here''s why you want to grind as you go: Once coffee has been roasted, oxygen becomes its mortal enemy and immediately the flavors in the oils begin to evaporate and the bean begins to turn sour. This is why coffee beans arrive in air-tight packages protected from all that nasty oxygen. Furthermore, when you grind the coffee, you compromise the ''housing'' for all this flavor and add more surface area for the beans to spoil giving the ground coffee a very, very short shelf life. So, only purchase as much coffee as you will drink in a week, keep it sealed in its original package or a canister, and grind as you go. Side note: don''t keep your beans in the fridge or freezer. Doing this doesn''t prolong its life, in fact, you make the coffee worse because it will absorb all those lovely aromas that are floating around in there (salmon flavored Kona, anyone?). Keep the beans at room temperature and you will be good.\r\n5.Proportion. \r\nThis is going to depend on you and your taste buds, actually. A general rule is one tablespoon per cup. A lot of places talk about proportions in grams and use quite a bit more than what I''m telling you to, but not too many of us have an accurate kitchen scale laying around, so forget that. A typical french press holds 8 cups of liquid, therefore use 8 tbs. If I''m in an economical mood I sometimes do 7 tbs to the 8 cups, but any less than that would leave your coffee tasting pretty watered down. You can up it a bit if you really want an intense flavor, but I wouldn''t go more than 1 or 2 tablespoons over that. \r\n6.Temperature (Water again) \r\nGet that water hot! An electric kettle works great if you have one, but use some method of boiling your water even if it''s in a saucepan. The target temp is around 200 degrees Fahrenheit, so right after the water hits a boil let it settle down and then pour into the press making sure to saturate all the grounds. Don''t burn the coffee! \r\n7.Time it!\r\nIt''s really important for the coffee and water to mix promiscuously allowing the oils to saturate and brew for the right amount of time. 4 minutes gets this done. If you are really striving for that cup of perfection, pour the water evenly over the grounds and fill the press a quarter full. Let the grounds then sit for a minute and “bloom”, then at the end of the minute add the rest of the water and stir. If you don''t want to do that, just pour the water in all at once and give it a good stir. \r\n8.Plunge it! \r\nWhen four minutes is up, drive all the grounds to the bottom with the plunger. In most cases the plunger works effectively to the point you don''t get any grounds in your cup. Even if you do get a couple have no fear, they are not out to get you. \r\n9.Drink it! \r\nEnjoy this beautiful beverage, you deserve it! Does this seem like a lot of work? Let''s think about it: depending on the elevation where you live, it takes somewhere around 2 to 4 minutes for water to boil. So what I do during that time is get the water heating up and then I grab all my stuff: the press (sometimes I clean it from the last time), grind the coffee, add it to the press, grab my cups, etc. and by the time everything is together (usually with time to spare) the water is ready, I pour, and I set my timer to 4 minutes. You can do the math, it''s about six to eight minutes from start to finish. That''s just about the same time as a conventional brewer! \r\n\r\nBelow is a video I made to also walk you through the process in case something I wrote didn''t quite make sense. Enjoy :-)', 'Make Good Coffee @ Home: French Press Style', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '563-revision-2', '', '', '2011-02-09 16:07:22', '2011-02-09 16:07:22', '', 563, 'http://coffeebot.co/coffee-shop-reviews/563-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
