per cup. A lot of places talk about proportions in grams and use quite a bit more than what I''m telling you to, but not too many of us have an accurate kitchen scale laying around, so forget that. A typical french press holds 8 cups of liquid, therefore use 8 tbs. If I''m in an economical mood I sometimes do 7 tbs to the 8 cups, but any less than that would leave your coffee tasting pretty watered down. You can up it a bit if you really want an intense flavor, but I wouldn''t go more than 1 or 2 tablespoons over that. \r\n<span class="first-words">Temperature (Water again) </span>\r\nGet that water hot! An electric kettle works great if you have one, but use some method of boiling your water even if it''s in a saucepan. The target temp is around 200 degrees Fahrenheit, so right after the water hits a boil let it settle down and then pour into the press making sure to saturate all the grounds. Don''t burn the coffee! \r\n<span class="first-words">Time it!</span>\r\nIt''s really important for the coffee and water to mix promiscuously allowing the oils to saturate and brew for the right amount of time. 4 minutes gets this done. If you are really striving for that cup of perfection, pour the water evenly over the grounds and fill the press a quarter full. Let the grounds then sit for a minute and “bloom”, then at the end of the minute add the rest of the water and stir. If you don''t want to do that, just pour the water in all at once and give it a good stir. \r\n<span class="first-words">Plunge it! </span>\r\nWhen four minutes is up, drive all the grounds to the bottom with the plunger. In most cases the plunger works effectively to the point you don''t get any grounds in your cup. Even if you do get a couple have no fear, they are not out to get you. \r\n<span class="first-words">Drink it! </span>\r\nEnjoy this beautiful beverage, you deserve it! Does this seem like a lot of work? Let''s think about it: depending on the elevation where you live, it takes somewhere around 2 to 4 minutes for water to boil. So what I do during that time is get the water heating up and then I grab all my stuff: the press (sometimes I clean it from the last time), grind the coffee, add it to the press, grab my cups, etc. and by the time everything is together (usually with time to spare) the water is ready, I pour, and I set my timer to 4 minutes. You can do the math, it''s about six to eight minutes from start to finish. That''s just about the same time as a conventional brewer! \r\n\r\nBelow is a video I made to also walk you through the process in case something I wrote didn''t quite make sense. Enjoy <span class', 'Make Good Coffee at Home: French Press Style', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '563-revision-7', '', '', '2011-02-09 16:17:38', '2011-02-09 16:17:38', '', 563, 'http://coffeebot.co/coffee-shop-reviews/563-revision-7/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
