(595, 1, '2011-03-03 15:46:38', '2011-03-03 15:46:38', '<script src="http://connect.facebook.net/en_US/all.js#xfbml=1"></script><fb:like show_faces="true" width="450"></fb:like>\n\n<div id="rating-block">\n[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="3.75" cat1detail="The right ingredients for good coffee" cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="3.5" cat2detail="inspirational and chill"]\n<table id="info">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td class="title">Features <a title="key" href="http://coffeebot.co/about-2/symbol-key/">(Key)</a></td>\n<td><span class="no-atm">No ATM</span><span class="no-alcohol">No Alcohol</span><span class="no-music">Live Music</span><span class="free-parking">Free Parking</span><span class="yes-food">Food is Served</span><span class="yes-wifi">Free Wifi</span><span class="manual">Manual Espresso Machine</span>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class="address">Mon - Fri</td>\n<td class="address">6:30am-10:00pm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class="address">Sat - Sun</td>\n<td class="address">7:00am-10:00pm</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class="address">501 E 19th Ave, Denver, CO 80203</td>\n<td class="phone">720.519.4681</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class="website"><a href="http://tridentcafe.com">Website</a></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</div>\n\n<a href="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/fluid.jpg"><img src="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/fluid.jpg" alt="fluid coffee bar" title="fluid coffee bar" width="525" height="199" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-592" /></a>\n\nA friend mentioned a place in uptown Denver that was attempting to re-define the coffee shop experience. “Redefine, eh?”. This is a place I had to visit. “Redefine(ing)” can be dangerous. Bot1 once tried to redefine rock. That''s how the world got prog-rock. Hopefully the coffee shop ''redefinement'' turns out a bit better. Bot1 was also excited to visit since there were computers he could use instead of relying on his 28k on-board modem to download 25 minute drum solos. So, we headed for the shop and arrived barely out of the shadows of downtown''s skyscrapers in an uncomfortably sterile neighborhood of condos and street shops.\n\nMy first impression of the place was positive and not at all what I expected after checking the shop''s website (which doesn''t do the place any justice). The shop was packed with city peeps when we arrived and I wound my way through tables and urbanites to the counter where I was welcomed by a large overhead menu and a not so welcoming, too-cool-for-school barista. \n\nI ordered a double espresso ($1.80) and Bot1 went for the mocha (medium:$3.50). The espresso was presented in a demitasse and I couldn''t wait to have my first sip. Once again, I stumbled on a place serving Novo coffee and was eager to see how it emerged from the machine. The first sip flashed with a bright acidity that yielded a complex cluster of flavors reminding me a bit of peanut butter—I was happy. It wasn''t the best espresso I''ve had but as the foundation to the rest of the beverages it was quality nonetheless. The mocha was fairly good as well (I sneaked a sip while Bot1 configured his IP address) although it was a bit sweet. It''s also worth noting that this truly is a good place for the coffee aficionado since I saw numerous french presses and am pretty sure some pourover coffee magic. \n\nWhat really makes Fluid Coffee tick is what I mentioned in the beginning of this post: coffee shop ''redefinement-ation-ing''. There is an abundance of places to sit, relax, work, and plug in. This is no internet cafe of the old days when shifty old guys hovered over bulky computers that were crammed against the walls of dingy, fluorescent-lit rooms sipping over-extracted, stale coffee. Instead you have flat panels, windows (so you''re not completely cut off from the world), shifty lawyers instead of shifty old guys, and superb coffee. Okay, I concede a bit of redefining. Fluid coffee has filled every nook with something for the customer: books, magazines, art, computers, and a [new] room full of tables that you can reserve for yourself or your team. You also don''t have to be without those office amenities if you are working remotely. For a fee, you are able to print and copy your top secret documents or the next great American novel. There is even a large column right next to the counter plastered with adverts and business cards so you can get ye-self out there and get discovered. Finally, I found the atmosphere fairly inspirational: multicolored walls, comfortable seating, clutter, conversational murmur, and a diversity of patrons. It''s the sort of place Bot1 and I can fit in with no brow-raising—it''s truly a neighborhood coffee shop. \n\nSo, does it redefine the coffee shop experience? They certainly make it easy for the incognito professional to have place to work, serve outstanding coffee, and manage to do all this without being a creepy internet cafe. Fluid coffee has found a great mix of community, casual, and professional. At the same time, it''s still only a coffee shop: one that neither wowed or excited me, but one that I most definitely will recommend and visit again...and again. \n\n<p style="text-align: center;">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\n', 'Fluid Coffee Bar', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '589-revision-4', '', '', '2011-03-03 15:46:38', '2011-03-03 15:46:38', '', 589, 'http://coffeebot.co/coffee-shop-reviews/589-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
