ng in the adjacent neighborhoods, or you might find yourself the proud owner of 2 parking tickets—in the same envelope, no less!). In addition, there are a couple bike racks out front, but judging from the many bikes chained to every railing along the street, these aren’t quite adequate for the demand.  I highly recommend visiting this café in the summer, when Boulder’s population decreases by about 20, 000. <span class="end-icon-bot6">END</span>\n\n[mappress mapid="14"]\n<p style="text-align: center">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\n', 'Buchanan’s Coffee Pub', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '610-revision-3', '', '', '2011-04-23 15:35:07', '2011-04-23 15:35:07', '', 610, 'http://coffeebot.co/coffee-shop-reviews/610-revision-3/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(612, 2, '2011-04-23 15:34:07', '2011-04-23 15:34:07', '\n\n<div>\n[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="2" cat1detail="Not Incredible" cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="2" cat2detail="Summed up: college-ness"]\n<table id="info">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td class="title">Features <a title="key" href="http://coffeebot.co/about-2/symbol-key/">(Key)</a></td>\n<td><span class="no-atm">No ATM</span><span class="no-alcohol">No Alcohol</span><span class="no-music">Live Music</span><span class="paid-parking">Paid Parking</span><span class="yes-food">Food is Served</span><span class="yes-wifi">Free Wifi</span><span class="manual">Manual Espresso Machine</span>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class="address">1301 Pennsylvania Ave, Boulder, CO 80302</td>\n<td class="phone">303.440.0222</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td class="website"><a href="http://www.fluidcoffeebar.com/">Website</a></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</div>\n\n\n<span class="first-words">I’d love to describe in vivid detail</span> the décor of Buchanan’s Coffee Pub, but my initial impression was only of stale incense swirling amongst a wall of undergrads. Fortunately, Bot1 tends to swear in binary, or I’m certain we would have been kicked out before paying for our coffee (12 oz. Americano= $2.22). Fighting through the crowd, we claimed the only available table—on the patio, next to an enthusiastic dance major (aside: we soon learned that “super” has worked its way back into the English vernacular with a vengeance, at which point Bot1 nearly short-circuited). \nBuchanan’s patio flanks the front door, facing west toward the busy intersection of Pennsylvania and Broadway, and the University of Colorado. This arrangement creates a prime basking/people-watching location in the afternoon, but if you forget your sun block, you’ll be the proud owner of a highly awkward “half-face sunburn.” There’s a lot to see, as “the hill” is home to many strange creatures, including (but not limited to) religious recruiters, social advocates, and various strains of hippie. In addition, an unfortunately gangly “sk8rboi” in lime green “jeggings” is forever imprinted on my mind—I wish I were kidding. Those who insist on conversing above the ruckus eventually resort to shouting and, consequently, must suffer the judgment of the other customers (I dedicate this paragraph to the table of passionate poli-sci majors who were laboring under the communal delusion that the opinions they were shouting at one another were, somehow, different. But I digress).\n\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee</span> Buchanan’s either servers Silver Canyon coffee or they stole their cups. Regardless, the espresso is medium-light, with a slightly bitter aftertaste (even with a touch of cream in it). My Americano was neither amazing nor unique, but having tasted the brown sludge for sale in the UMC, it’s worth the trek across campus. In addition to coffee, Buchanan’s sells pastries, gluten-free snacks, bagels, and (curiously) fair-trade crafts and jewelry.\n\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere</span> Eventually, a horde of people vacated the café lobby and Bot1 and I moved inside. I’d have to call Buchanan’s atmosphere “manufactured urban.” Local artwork and framed music posters decorate the walls, interspersed with intentionally exposed brick. Dozens of outlets run along the counters on three walls, which means that students (and visitors from the Boulder International Hostel just down the street) will move in here for hours at a time (the on-line printer and free-wifi probably add to the appeal). It’s bright, and the bluegrass/folk music sets a nice tone, but so many tables cram together that customers are constantly in each other’s  conversations (this might be fine for some, but Bot1 jumped in uninvited with “Heidegger, Derrida, and a duck walk into a bar . . .”). \n\n\n<span class="first-words">The End</span>There is paid parking in the lot across the street, or at meters along the block (beware parking in the adjacent neighborhoods, or you might find yourself the proud owner of 2 parking tickets—in the same envelope, no less!). In addition, there are a couple bike racks out front, but judging from the many bikes chained to every railing along the street, these aren’t quite adequate for the demand.  I highly recommend visiting this café in the summer, when Boulder’s population decreases by about 20, 000. <span class="end-icon-bot6">END</span>\n\n\n<p style="text-align: center">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n<a href="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/fluid.jpg"><img src="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/fluid.jpg" alt="fluid coffee bar" width="525" height="199" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-592" /></a>\n\n\n<a href="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/fluid.jpg"><img src="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/fluid.jpg" alt="fluid coffee bar" width="525" height="199" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-592" /></a>\n\n<span class="first-words">A friend mentioned a place in uptown Denver that was attempting to re-define the coffee shop experience.</span> “Redefine, eh?”. This is a place I had to visit. “Redefine(ing)” can be dangerous. Bot1 once tried to redefine rock. That''s how the world got prog-rock. Hopefully the coffee shop ''redefinement'' turns out a bit better. Bot1 was also excited to visit since there were computers he could use instead of relying on his 28k on-board modem to download 25 minute drum solos. So, we headed for the shop and arrived barely out of the shadows of downtown''s skyscrapers in an uncomfortably sterile neighborhood of condos and street shops.\n\nMy first impression of the place was positive and not at all what I expected after checking the shop''s website (which doesn''t do the place any justice). It was packed with city peeps when we arrived and I wound my way through tables and urbanites to the counter where I was welcomed by a large overhead menu and a not so welcoming, too-cool-for-school barista. \n\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee. </span>I ordered a double espresso ($1.80) and Bot1 went for the mocha (medium:$3.50). The espresso was presented in a demitasse and I couldn''t wait to have my first sip. Once again, I stumbled on a place serving Novo coffee and was eager to see how it emerged from the machine. The first sip flashed with a bright acidity that yielded a complex cluster of flavors reminding me a bit of peanut butter—I was happy. It wasn''t the best espresso I''ve had but as the foundation to the rest of the beverages it was quality nonetheless. The mocha was fairly good as well (I sneaked a sip while Bot1 configured his IP address) although it was a bit sweet. It''s also worth noting that this truly is a good place for the coffee aficionado since I saw numerous french presses and am pretty sure some pourover coffee magic. \n\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere. </span>What really makes Fluid Coffee tick is what I mentioned in the beginning of this post: coffee shop ''redefinement-ation-ing''. There is an abundance of places to sit, relax, work, and plug in. This is no internet cafe of the old days when shifty old guys hovered over bulky computers that were crammed against the walls of dingy, fluorescent-lit rooms sipping over-extracted, stale coffee. Instead you have flat panels, windows (so you''re not completely cut off from the world), shifty lawyers instead of shifty old guys, and superb coffee. Okay, I concede a bit of redefining. Fluid coffee has filled every nook with something for the customer: books, magazines, art, computers, and a [new] room full of tables that you can reserve for yourself or your team. You also don''t have to be without those office amenities if you are working remotely. For a fee, you are able to print and copy your top secret documents or the next great American novel. There is even a large column right next to the counter plastered with adverts and business cards so you can get ye-self out there and get discovered. Finally, I found the atmosphere fairly inspirational: multicolored walls, comfortable seating, clutter, conversational murmur, and a diversity of patrons did well to get the juices flowing. It''s the sort of place Bot1 and I can fit in with no brow-raising—it''s truly a neighborhood coffee shop. \n\n<span class="first-words">The End. </span>So, does it redefine the coffee shop experience? They certainly make it easy for the incognito professional to have place to work, serve outstanding coffee, and manage to do all this without being a creepy internet cafe. Fluid coffee has found a great mix of community, casual, and professional. At the same time, it''s still only a coffee shop: one that neither wowed or excited me, but one that I most definitely will recommend to others and visit again...and again. <span class="end-icon-bot2">END</span>\n[mappress mapid="13"]\n<p style="text-align: center">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\n', 'Buchanan’s Coffee Pub', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '610-revision-2', '', '', '2011-04-23 15:34:07', '2011-04-23 15:34:07', '', 610, 'http://coffeebot.co/coffee-shop-reviews/610-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
