uding (but not limited to) religious recruiters, social advocates, and various strains of hippie. In addition, an unfortunately gangly “sk8rboi” in lime green “jeggings” is forever imprinted on my mind—I wish I were kidding. Those who insist on conversing above the ruckus eventually resort to shouting and, consequently, must suffer the judgment of the other customers (I dedicate this paragraph to the table of passionate poli-sci majors who were laboring under the communal delusion that the opinions they were shouting at one another were, somehow, different. But I digress).\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee</span> Buchanan’s either servers Silver Canyon coffee or they stole their cups. Regardless, the espresso is medium-light, with a slightly bitter aftertaste (even with a touch of cream in it). My Americano was neither amazing nor unique, but having tasted the brown sludge for sale in the UMC, it’s worth the trek across campus. In addition to coffee, Buchanan’s sells pastries, gluten-free snacks, bagels, and (curiously) fair-trade crafts and jewelry.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere</span> Eventually, a horde of people vacated the café lobby and Bot1 and I moved inside. I’d have to call Buchanan’s atmosphere “manufactured urban.” Local artwork and framed music posters decorate the walls, interspersed with intentionally exposed brick. Dozens of outlets run along the counters on three walls, which means that students (and visitors from the Boulder International Hostel just down the street) will move in here for hours at a time (the on-line printer and free-wifi probably add to the appeal). It’s bright, and the bluegrass/folk music sets a nice tone, but so many tables cram together that customers are constantly in each other’s  conversations (this might be fine for some, but Bot1 jumped in uninvited with “Heidegger, Derrida, and a duck walk into a bar . . .”). \r\n\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The End</span>There is paid parking in the lot 