(631, 1, '2011-08-02 13:57:26', '2011-08-02 13:57:26', '<a href="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/buchanans.jpg"><img src="http://coffeebot.co/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/buchanans.jpg" alt="buchanans" width="525" height="199" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-622" /></a>\r\n<div>\r\n[easyreview title="The Stats" cat1title="Coffee Quality" cat1rating="4" cat1detail="Good coffee done well" cat2title="Atmosphere" cat2rating="3" cat2detail="cluttered artsy charm"]\r\n<table id="info">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="title">Features <a title="key" href="http://coffeebot.co/about-2/symbol-key/">(Key)</a></td>\r\n<td><span class="no-atm">No ATM</span><span class="yes-alcohol">Alcohol</span><span class="yes-music">Live Music</span><span class="free-parking">Free Parking</span><span class="yes-food">Food is Served</span><span class="yes-wifi">Free Wifi</span><span class="manual">Manual Espresso Machine</span>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class="address">908 Main Street, Louisville, CO 80027</td>\r\n<td class="phone">303.665.9761</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<span class="first-words">Bot1 was bored and complaining that he hadn''t exercised his french algorithms in a while and they needed flexing. I tried to disagree by making the point French algorithms should just stay where they are, but after warning me he''d actually move to France if I didn''t let him, I traipsed him down to Cafe de Paris in Old Town(e) Louisville, Colorado to get it out of his system. \r\n\r\nAs one might expect, I figured this place was just another “in name only” joint that really had nothing to do with Paris at all (not that I''m an authority on the city). I was right, well, almost. When we walked in we were met with the croonings of a geeky jazz quartet—and for a brief moment it did indeed feel like a Paris cafe in the fifties. Or it at least felt like I''ve seen them portrayed in the movies. This was a nice surprise, and Bot1 approved so we decided to stay.\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Coffee</span> I edged around the double bass and did my best to remember my high school french. When I realized I couldn''t remember any of it, I ordered my coffee (in English) and took a corner table nestled under a bohemian lamp and beside a large picture window overlooking the bustling street. Once again, we''d stumbled on yet another shop serving Novo roasted coffee, which indicated off-the-bat that the desire for quality was present. And indeed, upon my first sip, that was the case. Full dimension, balanced flavor and lingering sweetness characterized the nectar that emerged from the Rancilio manual espresso machine. \r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The Atmosphere</span> I was very comfortable sitting in this comfortably-cramp shop. The evening was warm and the sidewalk seating appealed to me, but Bot1 insisted we sit inside, and if you are a frequent reader of these posts, you know he gets his way. Six round tables fit where only four should go, but somehow it worked and I didn''t feel too claustrophobic. Perhaps it was the Bohemian flavor from the painted walls to the paintings on the walls, or the Victorian lamp shades, or all of these, but it was definitely the kind of place I could spend some time. In fact, you could get really comfortable for a long time since beer and wine are also served. I love coffee shops that do this—you''ve got all the bases covered. The shop definitely goes lengths to have that European vibe, down to elements you can''t necessarily control. Such as the hipster clientele who, as Bot1 and I sat and sipped our coffees and tapping our toes and metallic phalanges to the music, sketched and painted meaningful and earnest doodles at their tables. Had we stumbled across a sliver of the Paris art scene, one that stowed away on the Titanic, perhaps, only to be set adrift somehow surfacing upstream in Colorado? Okay, well that''s going a little too far, but needless to say it was a fun, and perhaps even inspiring atmosphere to be in. \r\n\r\n\r\n<span class="first-words">The End</span>Don''t let me steer you wrong with my emphasis on coffee side of things, though. These guys are a full on “bistro” serving up a variety of tasty foods and desserts, even for those with slightly more high maintenance diets. I would however steer clear of their pastry items. I''ve been a few times and each time the bakery good whether a scone or sweet bread was dry almost to the point of stale. Don''t spend the money. Aside from that, overall, this cafe does what it should: calms, inspires, satisfies the taste buds, and makes you want to return for more. <span class="end-icon-bot2">END</span>\r\n\r\n[mappress mapid="15"]\r\n\r\n<p style="text-align: center">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\r\n', 'Cafe de Paris ', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '627-revision-3', '', '', '2011-08-02 13:57:26', '2011-08-02 13:57:26', '', 627, 'http://coffeebot.co/coffee-shop-reviews/627-revision-3/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
