ed. I love coffee shops that do this—you''ve got all the bases covered. The shop definitely goes lengths to have that European vibe, down to elements you can''t necessarily control. Such as the hipster clientele who, as Bot1 and I sat and sipped our coffees and tapping our toes and metallic phalanges to the music, sketched and painted meaningful and earnest doodles at their tables. Had we stumbled across a sliver of the Paris art scene, one that stowed away on the Titanic, perhaps, only to be set adrift somehow surfacing upstream in Colorado? Okay, well that''s going a little too far, but needless to say it was a fun, and perhaps even inspiring atmosphere to be in. \n\n\n<span class="first-words">The End</span> Don''t let me steer you wrong with my emphasis on coffee side of things, though. These guys are a full on “bistro” serving up a variety of tasty foods and desserts, even for those with slightly more high maintenance diets. I would however steer clear of their pastry items. I''ve been a few times and each time the bakery good whether a scone or sweet bread was dry almost to the point of stale. Don''t spend the money. Aside from that, overall, this cafe does what it should: calms, inspires, satisfies the taste buds, and makes you want to return for more. <span class="end-icon-bot2">END</span>\n\n[mappress mapid="15"]\n\n<p style="text-align: center">[ad#Google Adsense Post Ad]</p>\n', 'Cafe de Paris ', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '627-revision-11', '', '', '2011-08-02 17:38:05', '2011-08-02 17:38:05', '', 627, 'http://coffeebot.co/coffee-shop-reviews/627-revision-11/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
